{"title_page": "Paradise Dam (Montana)", "text_new": "{{Infobox dam\n| name = Paradise Dam\n| image = Paradise Dam MT1.jpg\n| image_caption = Paradise Dam as proposed\n| name_official = \n| dam_crosses = [[Clark Fork River]] and [[Flathead River]]\n| res_name = Paradise Reservoir\n| res_capacity_total = {{convert|4080000|acre.ft|km3}}\n| res_catchment = \n| res_surface = {{convert|103|sqmi|km2}}\n| location = [[Sanders County, Montana|Sanders County]], near [[Paradise, Montana|Paradise]], [[Montana|Montana, USA]]\n| operator = [[U.S. Army Corps of Engineers]]\n| dam_length = {{Convert|3750|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n| dam_height = {{Convert|250|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n| dam_width_base = \n| dam_volume = \n| spillway_type = [[Floodgate|Gated]] spillway\n| spillway_capacity = \n| construction_began = \n| opening = \n| plant_operator = \n| plant_turbines = 8 x 72 MW turbines, 6 additional to be installed later\n| plant_capacity = 576 [[Watt#Megawatt|MW]] initially<br>1000 [[Watt#Megawatt|MW]] in a later phase\n| plant_annual_gen = \n| location_map = Montana\n| coordinates = {{coord|47|24|57|N|114|50|00|W|type:landmark_source:gnis|display=inline,title}}\n| status = Cancelled\n}}\n\n'''Paradise Dam''' was a proposed dam on the [[Clark Fork River]] in [[Montana]]. It was proposed by the [[U.S. Army Corps of Engineers]] as an alternative to the construction of [[Glacier View Dam]] on the western boundary of [[Glacier National Park (U.S.)|Glacier National Park]], to capture the flow of the [[Flathead River]]. The earth embankment dam was planned to be about {{convert|250|ft|m}} high, impounding a reservoir of {{convert|4080000|acre.ft|km3}}. While it was viewed as a desirable power generation and water storage project by the Corps of Engineers, it was opposed by those it would displace from towns and productive agricultural lands, and was never built.\n\n==Proposal==\nThe dam was proposed in the 1940s as an alternative to the controversial Glacier View Dam, which was strenuously opposed by the [[National Park Service]] and conservation organizations as an intrusion into national park lands. It would have inundated {{convert|9000|acre|ha}} of already-irrigated and farmed lands, with the reservoir extending {{convert|49|mi|km}} up the Clark Fork and {{convert|72|mi|km}} up the Flathead to the base of [[Kerr Dam]]. The project required the relocation of roads, rail lines and houses and businesses in several communities. The cost in 1950 was estimated at $265,569,000.<ref name=ace1>{{cite web|title=Columbia River and Tributaries, Northwestern United States|publisher=Army Corps of Engineers|page=155|date=March 20, 1950}}</ref>\n\nAlternative sites at The Plains, five miles downstream from [[Plains, Montana]], and the Weeks site, three miles downstream from the Plains site, were examined but rejected on grounds of poor foundation conditions.  Three other sites, Knowles (river mile 4), Perma (river mile 11) and Oxbow (river mile 41) were rejected on similar grounds.<ref name=ace156>Corps of Engineers 1950 Columbia River and Tributaries Report, p. 156</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nWhile the project was supported by some local organizations, local opposition was intense, focusing on displacement of productive agriculture and populations and intrusion on Indian rights. Land replacement compensation for the [[National Bison Range]] was considered likely. As a result, planning was not pursued and the project remained an alternative to other project farther upstream.  In the event, none of the proposed reservoirs in the area were built, apart from [[Hungry Horse Dam|Hungry Horse Reservoir]].<ref name=ace156/>\n\n==Description==\nThe complex arrangement placed a {{convert|250|ft|m|adj=on}} earth embankment across the main channel of the river, diverting the flow to the west, where a straight intake dam structure extending parallel to the riverbed on the riverbank  would receive water for the powerplant. A separate curved spillway dam would be located downstream from the intake dam. At the end of the diverted channel an embankment saddle dam would seal the channel. The powerplant was planned to have an initial capacity of 576 MW with eight 72MW units, expandable to 1000 MW with six more generators in the future.<ref name=ace-plan>Corps of Engineers 1950 Columbia River and Tributaries Report, Paradise Dam schematic plan</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|Paradise Dam (Montana)}}\n\n[[Category:United States Army Corps of Engineers proposed dams]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Sanders County, Montana]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox dam\n| name                 =Paradise Dam\n| image                =Paradise Dam MT1.jpg\n| image_caption        =Paradise Dam as proposed\n| name_official        =\n| dam_crosses          = [[Clark Fork River]] and [[Flathead River]]\n| res_name             = Paradise Reservoir\n| res_capacity_total   = {{convert|4080000|acre.ft|km3}}\n| res_catchment        = \n| res_surface          = {{convert|103|sqmi|km2}}\n| location             =[[Sanders County, Montana|Sanders County]], near [[Paradise, Montana|Paradise]], [[Montana|Montana, USA]]\n| operator             = [[U.S. Army Corps of Engineers]]\n| dam_length           ={{Convert|3750|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n| dam_height           ={{Convert|250|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n| dam_width_base       =\n| dam_volume           = \n| spillway_type        =  [[Floodgate|Gated]] spillway\n| spillway_capacity    = \n| construction_began   =Proposal only\n| opening              = \n| plant_operator       =\n| plant_turbines       = 8 x 72 MW turbines, 6 additional to be installed later\n| plant_capacity       = 576 [[Watt#Megawatt|MW]] initially<br>1000 [[Watt#Megawatt|MW]] in a later phase\n| plant_annual_gen     = \n| location_map         = Montana\n| coordinates          = {{coord|47|24|57|N|114|50|00|W|type:landmark_source:gnis|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Paradise Dam''' was a proposed dam on the [[Clark Fork River]] in [[Montana]]. It was proposed by the [[U.S. Army Corps of Engineers]] as an alternative to the construction of [[Glacier View Dam]] on the western boundary of [[Glacier National Park (U.S.)|Glacier National Park]], to capture the flow of the [[Flathead River]]. The earth embankment dam was planned to be about {{convert|250|ft|m}} high, impounding a reservoir of {{convert|4080000|acre.ft|km3}}. While it was viewed as a desirable power generation and water storage project by the Corps of Engineers, it was opposed by those it would displace from towns and productive agricultural lands, and was never built.\n\n==Proposal==\nThe dam was proposed in the 1940s as an alternative to the controversial Glacier View Dam, which was strenuously opposed by the [[National Park Service]] and conservation organizations as an intrusion into national park lands. It would have inundated {{convert|9000|acre|ha}} of already-irrigated and farmed lands, with the reservoir extending {{convert|49|mi|km}} up the Clark Fork and {{convert|72|mi|km}} up the Flathead to the base of [[Kerr Dam]]. The project required the relocation of roads, rail lines and houses and businesses in several communities. The cost in 1950 was estimated at $265,569,000.<ref name=ace1>{{cite web|title=Columbia River and Tributaries, Northwestern United States|publisher=Army Corps of Engineers|page=155|date=March 20, 1950}}</ref>\n\nAlternative sites at The Plains, five miles downstream from [[Plains, Montana]], and the Weeks site, three miles downstream from the Plains site, were examined but rejected on grounds of poor foundation conditions.  Three other sites, Knowles (river mile 4), Perma (river mile 11) and Oxbow (river mile 41) were rejected on similar grounds.<ref name=ace156>Corps of Engineers 1950 Columbia River and Tributaries Report, p. 156</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nWhile the project was supported by some local organizations, local opposition was intense, focusing on displacement of productive agriculture and populations and intrusion on Indian rights. Land replacement compensation for the [[National Bison Range]] was considered likely. As a result, planning was not pursued and the project remained an alternative to other project farther upstream.  In the event, none of the proposed reservoirs in the area were built, apart from [[Hungry Horse Dam|Hungry Horse Reservoir]].<ref name=ace156/>\n\n==Description==\nThe complex arrangement placed a {{convert|250|ft|m|adj=on}} earth embankment across the main channel of the river, diverting the flow to the west, where a straight intake dam structure extending parallel to the riverbed on the riverbank  would receive water for the powerplant. A separate curved spillway dam would be located downstream from the intake dam. At the end of the diverted channel an embankment saddle dam would seal the channel. The powerplant was planned to have an initial capacity of 576 MW with eight 72MW units, expandable to 1000 MW with six more generators in the future.<ref name=ace-plan>Corps of Engineers 1950 Columbia River and Tributaries Report, Paradise Dam schematic plan</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|Paradise Dam (Montana)}}\n\n[[Category:United States Army Corps of Engineers proposed dams]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Sanders County, Montana]]\n", "name_user": "Macquaria", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed status", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paradise_Dam_(Montana)"}
{"title_page": "Alberto Malesani", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{lead too short|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n | name = Alberto Malesani\n | image = Malesani2010.jpg\n | caption = Malesani with [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]] in 2010\n | fullname = Alberto Malesani\n | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1954|6|5|df=y}}\n | birth_place = [[Verona]], Italy\n | currentclub = \n | position = [[Midfielder]]\n | height = 1.79m\n | youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = Audace S. Michele\n | youthyears2 = 1970 | youthclubs2 = [[Vicenza Calcio|Vicenza]]\n | years1 = | clubs1 = Audace S. Michele | caps1 = | goals1 = \n | manageryears1 = 1987\u20131990 | managerclubs1 = [[A.C. ChievoVerona|Chievo]] (junior)\n | manageryears2 = 1990\u20131991 | managerclubs2 = Chievo (youth)\n | manageryears3 = 1991\u20131993 | managerclubs3 = Chievo (assistant)\n | manageryears4 = 1993\u20131997 | managerclubs4 = Chievo\n | manageryears5 = 1997\u20131998 | managerclubs5 = [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]]\n | manageryears6 = 1998\u20132001 | managerclubs6 = [[Parma F.C.|Parma]]\n | manageryears7 = 2001\u20132003 | managerclubs7 = [[Hellas Verona F.C.|Verona]]\n | manageryears8 = 2003\u20132004 | managerclubs8 = [[Modena F.C.|Modena]]\n | manageryears9 = 2005\u20132006 | managerclubs9 = [[Panathinaikos FC|Panathinaikos]]\n | manageryears10 = 2007     | managerclubs10 = [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]]\n | manageryears11 = 2007\u20132008| managerclubs11 = [[Empoli F.C.|Empoli]]\n | manageryears12 = 2009\u20132010| managerclubs12 = [[A.C. Siena|Siena]]\n | manageryears13 = 2010\u20132011| managerclubs13 = [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]]\n | manageryears14 = 2011     | managerclubs14 = [[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]]\n | manageryears15 = 2012     | managerclubs15 = Genoa\n | manageryears16 = 2013     | managerclubs16 = [[U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo|Palermo]]\n | manageryears17 = 2014     | managerclubs17 = [[U.S. Sassuolo Calcio|Sassuolo]]\n}}\n'''Alberto Malesani''' ({{IPA-it|al\u02c8b\u025brto male\u02c8za\u02d0ni}}; born 5 June 1954) is an Italian [[association football]] [[Association football manager|manager]] and former [[Association football|footballer]]. As a manager, he is mostly remembered for his successful spell with [[Parma F.C.|Parma]] during the late 90s, where he won the [[Coppa Italia]], the [[UEFA Cup]], and the [[Supercoppa Italiana]].\n\n==Career==\n===Early career and breakthrough at Chievo===\n[[Image:Malesani.jpg|thumb|A young Malesani during his first stint as Chievo head coach]]\nMalesani career as player was mostly spent on a [[Verona|Veronese]] amateur team Audace S. Michele, where he obtained a promotion from [[Serie D]] to [[Serie C]] in 1976\u201377, appearing fourteen times on that season.<ref>{{in lang|it}} [http://www.hellastory.net/pages/scheda.cfm?id=7D590D79-4854-12EA-BD663F99594DEB70 HELLASTORY.net | La Scheda di Alberto Malesani<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He retired from playing football at the age of 24, and worked at [[Canon (company)|Canon]] in [[Amsterdam]], where he studied the [[Ajax Amsterdam]] [[total football]] training methods.<ref>[http://www.tifonet.it/fiore/malesani/bio.htm Alberto Malesani \u2013 l'antipersonaggio (la biografia)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> His passion for coaching was so great, that on his honeymoon, he decided to go to [[Barcelona]] in order to watch [[Johan Cruijff]]'s coaching sessions at [[Barcelona FC]].\n \nMalesani left his job at Canon in 1990 order to pursue a coaching career at [[Serie C1]] team [[A.C. ChievoVerona|Chievo]] for the ''Allievi'' youth squad. In 1991, he is assistant of head coach [[Carlo De Angelis]] in the first team, and in 1993 he becomes head coach himself. His first season as head coach ended in a historical promotion to [[Serie B]] for then-unknown Chievo.\n\n===Fiorentina, Parma and UEFA Cup triumph===\nMalesani left Chievo in 1997, after three impressive Serie B seasons and a narrowly missed promotion in the Serie A league in order to become [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]]'s boss, in what was his first stint in the Italian top flight.\n\nA good Fiorentina season convinced [[Parma F.C.|Parma]] to appoint Malesani as new head coach in 1998, where he won a [[Coppa Italia]], a [[UEFA Cup]], an [[Italian Super Cup]] and obtained two fourth places before being sacked during the [[2000\u201301 Serie A|2000\u201301 season]].<ref name=auction>{{cite web|url=http://gazzettaworld.gazzetta.it/off-the-ball/malesani-bid-uefa-cup-parma/?refresh_ce-cp|title=Malesani bids for UEFA Cup in Parma auction|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|author1=Sumeet Paul|date=7 October 2015|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/63457/when-parma-ruled-europe|title=When Parma ruled Europe|publisher=Football Italia|author1=Dave Taylor|date=5 March 2015|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===From Verona to Panathinaikos and Udinese===\nAfter losing his job at Parma, Malesani then coached [[Hellas Verona F.C.|Verona]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hellasverona.it/news.php?id=473|title=E' UFFICIALE, ALBERTO MALESANI SARA' L'ALLENATORE DELL'HELLAS VERONA ANCHE NELLA STAGIONE 2002/2003|date=8 February 2002|accessdate=25 April 2014|publisher=Hellas Verona FC|language=Italian}}</ref> and [[Modena F.C.|Modena]], failing to save the clubs from relegation in both cases; successively he moved abroad to coach [[Greece|Greek]] side [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]]. Panathinaikos remains the club with the highest percentage of wins in Malesani's career to date (60%).\n\nMalesani was appointed coach of [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]] in January 2007, as replacement for [[Giovanni Galeone]]. He led his side to a not particularly impressive tenth place in the [[2006\u201307 Serie A]] final table, only seven points far from relegation, being not confirmed for the following season. On 27 November 2007 he was unveiled as [[Empoli F.C.|Empoli]]'s new head coach, replacing [[Luigi Cagni]].<ref name=\"cagni_sacked\">{{cite news|url=http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/nov26p.html |date=26 November 2007 |accessdate=27 November 2007 |publisher=Football Italia |title=Empoli axe Cagni |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071128121509/http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/nov26p.html |archivedate=28 November 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was axed on 31 March 2008 following a 2\u20130 home defeat to [[U.C. Sampdoria]] which left Empoli down in last place in the league table.<ref name=\"malesani_sacked\">{{cite news |title=L'Empoli licenzia Malesani. In panchina torna Cagni|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Squadre/Empoli/Primo_Piano/2008/03_Marzo/31/malesani.shtml |publisher= La Gazzetta dello Sport |date= 31 March 2008 |accessdate=31 March 2008 |language=Italian}}</ref>\n\n===From Siena to Bologna===\nOn 23 November 2009, he was appointed as the new head coach of [[A.C. Siena|Siena]], replacing [[Marco Baroni]].<ref name=\"malesani_siena\">{{cite news |url=http://www.acsiena.it/comunicatidetail.php3?id=8099|language=Italian |publisher=AC Siena |accessdate=23 November 2009 |date=23 November 2009 |title=Raggiunto l'accordo con Alberto Malesani}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> On 21 May 2010, was released by Siena.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.acsiena.it/dettaglionews_3.php?id=8433|title=SportReggio {{!}} Recensioni, Prezzi, Classifiche e News|website=SportReggio|language=it-IT|access-date=2018-09-15}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 September 2010, he signed a one-year contract for [[Bologna F.C.|Bologna]].<ref>[https://archive.is/20100905064049/http://www.bolognafc.it/it/news/pagine/9274/Malesani-%E2%80%9CFinalmente-sulla-panchina-del-Bologna%E2%80%9D.html Malesani: \u201cFinalmente sulla panchina del Bologna\u201d]</ref>\nAfter a successful season which saw his club finish in 16th place, six points clear of relegation, despite a three-point deduction for tax problems and running feuds over the club's ownership, Malesani was replaced by [[Pierpaolo Bisoli]] on 26 May 2011.<ref>[http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/26052011/58/serie-bologna-dump-malesani-bisoli.html Serie A - Bologna dump Malesani for Bisoli]</ref>\n\n===Genoa===\nOn 19 June 2011, [[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]] officially announced that Malesani would be the new first team head coach.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.genoacfc.it/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=12228&Itemid=31|title=ALBERTO MALESANI NUOVO ALLENATORE |date=19 June 2011|accessdate=19 June 2011|publisher=Genoa C.F.C. |language=Italian}}</ref> However, after Genoa was defeated 6-1 by Napoli, Malesani was fired.<ref>[http://www.chron.com/sports/article/Genoa-fires-coach-Malesani-hires-Marino-2420033.php]</ref> He returned to Genoa on 2 April 2012, taking over from [[Pasquale Marino]] who had previously replaced him only to be sacked a few months later.<ref name=\"malesani_back\">{{cite news|url=http://www.genoacfc.it/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14199&Itemid=31 |title=COMUNICATO STAMPA |date=2 April 2012|accessdate=3 April 2012|work=Genoa CFC}}</ref> His second stint as Genoa boss lasted however only twenty days, as he was sacked once again on 22 April after a 1\u20134 home loss to [[A.C. Siena|Siena]] that left Genoa one point shy of relegation, and led to massive protests from Genoa fans during the game.<ref name=\"decanio_genoa\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cittadigenova.com/Genova/Sport/Incubo-Genoa-Malesani-nuovamente-50639.aspx |title=Incubo Genoa/ Malesani nuovamente esonerato. Squadra a Gigi De Canio |date=22 April 2012 |accessdate=22 April 2012 |work=Citt\u00e0 di Genova |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407083252/http://www.cittadigenova.com/Genova/Sport/Incubo-Genoa-Malesani-nuovamente-50639.aspx |archivedate=7 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Palermo===\nOn 5 February 2013, Malesani was appointed as the manager of [[U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo|Palermo]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://football-italia.net/30395/official-malesani-joins-palermo|title=Official: Malesani joins Palermo {{!}} Football Italia|website=football-italia.net|access-date=2018-09-15}}</ref>\n\nHowever, after three matches in charge, on 24 February 2013 Malesani was relieved from his duties as the manager.<ref name=\"malesani-sacked-palermo\">{{cite news |publisher=US Citt\u00e0 di Palermo |language=Italian |accessdate=26 February 2013 |date=24 February 2013 |url=http://palermocalcio.it/it/1213/news/scheda.php?id=28121 |title=ESONERATO MALESANI, RICHIAMATO GASPERINI |trans-title=MALESANI SACKED, GASPERINI RECALLED |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130227012556/http://palermocalcio.it/it/1213/news/scheda.php?id=28121 |archive-date=27 February 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Sassuolo===\nOn 29 January 2014, it was announced Malesani has agreed to take over as new manager of the top-flight team [[U.S. Sassuolo Calcio|Sassuolo]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Malesani tasked with reviving Sassuolo fortunes|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=ita/news/newsid=2048399.html |publisher= UEFA.com |date= 29 January 2014 |accessdate=8 February 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|9 March 2014}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n!rowspan=2! width=100|Team\n!rowspan=2! width=50|Nat\n!rowspan=2! width=90|From\n!rowspan=2! width=90|To\n!colspan=8|Record\n|-\n!width=30|G\n!width=30|W\n!width=30|D\n!width=30|L\n!width=50|Win %\n!width=40|GF\n!width=40|GA\n!width=40|+/-\n|-\n|align=left|[[A.C. ChievoVerona|Chievo]]\n|{{flagicon|Italy}}\n|align=left|1 June 1993{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n|align=left|30 June 1997\n| 155 || 52 || 66 || 37 || {{#expr: 52/155 * 100 round 2}} ||170||140||+30\n|-\n|align=left|[[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]]\n|{{flagicon|Italy}}\n|align=left|1 July 1997{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n|align=left|30 June 1998{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n| 40 || 18 || 15 || 7 || {{#expr: 18/40 * 100 round 2}} ||74||41||+33\n|-\n|align=left|[[Parma F.C.|Parma]]\n|{{flagicon|Italy}}\n|align=left|1 July 1998{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n|align=left|8 January 2001{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n| 123 || 62 || 33 || 28 || {{#expr: 62/123 * 100 round 2}} ||211||125||+86\n|-\n|align=left|[[Hellas Verona F.C.|Verona]]\n|{{flagicon|Italy}}\n|align=left|4 July 2001{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n|align=left|10 June 2003{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n| 77 || 23 || 23 || 31 || {{#expr: 23/77 * 100 round 2}} ||88||101||\u221213\n|-\n|align=left|[[Modena F.C.|Modena]]\n|{{flagicon|Italy}}\n|align=left|10 June 2003{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n|align=left|22 March 2004{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n| 30 || 6 || 10 || 14 || {{#expr: 6/30 * 100 round 2}} ||25||39||\u221214\n|-\n|align=left|[[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]]\n|{{flagicon|Greece}}\n|align=left|16 February 2005{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n|align=left|15 May 2006{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n| 53 || 32 || 9 || 12 || {{#expr: 32/53 * 100 round 2}} ||74||52||+22\n|-\n|align=left|[[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]]\n|{{flagicon|Italy}}\n|align=left|16 January 2007{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n|align=left|30 June 2007{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n| 20 || 7 || 5 || 8 || {{#expr: 7/20 * 100 round 2}} ||32||34||\u22122\n|-\n|align=left|[[Empoli F.C.|Empoli]]\n|{{flagicon|Italy}}\n|align=left|26 November 2007{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n|align=left|31 March 2008{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n| 20 || 5 || 4 || 11 || {{#expr: 5/20 * 100 round 2}} ||22||30||\u22128\n|-\n|align=left|Siena\n|{{flagicon|Italy}}\n|align=left|23 November 2009{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n|align=left|21 May 2010{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n| 26 || 6 || 7 || 13 || {{#expr: 6/26 * 100 round 2}} ||29||47||\u221218\n|-\n|align=left|[[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]]\n|{{flagicon|Italy}}\n|align=left|1 September 2010{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n|align=left|26 May 2011{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n| 40 || 13 || 11 || 16 || {{#expr: 13/40 * 100 round 2}} ||42||56||\u221214\n|-\n|align=left|[[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]]\n|{{flagicon|Italy}}\n|align=left|19 June 2011{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n|align=left|22 December 2011{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n| 18 || 8 || 3 || 7 || {{#expr: 8/18 * 100 round 2}} ||27||29||\u22122\n|-\n|align=left|Genoa\n|{{flagicon|Italy}}\n|align=left|2 April 2012{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n|align=left|22 April 2012{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n| 3 || 0 || 2 || 1 || {{#expr: 0/3 * 100 round 2}} ||2||6||\u22124\n|-\n|align=left|[[U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo|Palermo]]\n|{{flagicon|Italy}}\n|align=left|5 February 2013{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n|align=left|24 February 2013{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n| 3 || 0 || 3 || 0 || {{#expr: 0/3 * 100 round 2}} ||2||2||0\n|-\n|align=left|[[U.S. Sassuolo Calcio|Sassuolo]]\n|{{flagicon|Italy}}\n|align=left|29 January 2014\n|align=left|3 March 2014\n| 6 || 0 || 1 || 5 || {{#expr: 0/6 * 100 round 2}} ||3||9||\u22126\n|-\n! colspan=4 style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:middle;\"|Total\n! 614 !! 232 !! 192 !! 190 !! {{#expr: 232/614 * 100 round 2}} !!801!!711!!+90\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Managerial===\n;Chievo (1993\u20131997)\n*[[Lega Pro Prima Divisione|Serie C1]] (1): [[1993\u201394 Serie C1|1993\u201394]]\n\n;Parma (1998\u20132001)<ref name=auction/>\n*[[Coppa Italia]] (1): [[1998\u201399 Coppa Italia|1998\u201399]]\n*[[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] (1): [[1998\u201399 UEFA Cup|1998\u201399]]\n*[[Supercoppa Italiana]] (1): [[1999 Supercoppa Italiana|1999]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of UEFA Cup winning managers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hellastory.net/pages/scheda.cfm?id=7D590D79-4854-12EA-BD663F99594DEB70 Profile of Alberto Malesani on Hellastory.net]\n\n{{UEFA Cup / Europa League winning managers}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= Alberto Malesani managerial positions\n|list1=\n{{A.C. ChievoVerona managers}}\n{{ACF Fiorentina managers}}\n{{Parma F.C. managers}}\n{{Hellas Verona F.C. managers}}\n{{Panathinaikos FC managers}}\n{{Udinese Calcio managers}}\n{{A.C. Siena managers}}\n{{Bologna F.C. 1909 managers}}\n{{Genoa C.F.C. managers}}\n{{U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo managers}}\n{{U.S. Sassuolo Calcio managers}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malesani, Alberto}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Verona]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:UEFA Cup winning managers]]\n[[Category:Udinese Calcio managers]]\n[[Category:Parma Calcio 1913 managers]]\n[[Category:ACF Fiorentina managers]]\n[[Category:Modena F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Panathinaikos F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:A.C. ChievoVerona managers]]\n[[Category:Empoli F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Robur Siena managers]]\n[[Category:Bologna F.C. 1909 managers]]\n[[Category:Genoa C.F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Italian football managers]]\n[[Category:L.R. Vicenza Virtus players]]\n[[Category:Superleague Greece managers]]\n[[Category:S.S.D. Palermo managers]]\n[[Category:U.S. Sassuolo Calcio managers]]\n[[Category:Serie A managers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Greece]]\n[[Category:Italian footballers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{lead too short|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n | name = Alberto Malesani\n | image = Malesani2010.jpg\n | caption = Malesani with [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]] in 2010\n | fullname = Alberto Malesani\n | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1954|6|5|df=y}}\n | birth_place = [[Verona]], Italy\n | currentclub = \n | position = [[Midfielder]]\n | height = 1.79m\n | youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = Audace S. Michele\n | youthyears2 = 1970 | youthclubs2 = [[Vicenza Calcio|Vicenza]]\n | years1 = | clubs1 = Audace S. Michele | caps1 = | goals1 = \n | manageryears1 = 1987\u20131990 | managerclubs1 = [[A.C. ChievoVerona|Chievo]] (junior)\n | manageryears2 = 1990\u20131991 | managerclubs2 = Chievo (youth)\n | manageryears3 = 1991\u20131993 | managerclubs3 = Chievo (assistant)\n | manageryears4 = 1993\u20131997 | managerclubs4 = Chievo\n | manageryears5 = 1997\u20131998 | managerclubs5 = [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]]\n | manageryears6 = 1998\u20132001 | managerclubs6 = [[Parma F.C.|Parma]]\n | manageryears7 = 2001\u20132003 | managerclubs7 = [[Hellas Verona F.C.|Verona]]\n | manageryears8 = 2003\u20132004 | managerclubs8 = [[Modena F.C.|Modena]]\n | manageryears9 = 2005\u20132006 | managerclubs9 = [[Panathinaikos FC|Panathinaikos]]\n | manageryears10 = 2007     | managerclubs10 = [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]]\n | manageryears11 = 2007\u20132008| managerclubs11 = [[Empoli F.C.|Empoli]]\n | manageryears12 = 2009\u20132010| managerclubs12 = [[A.C. Siena|Siena]]\n | manageryears13 = 2010\u20132011| managerclubs13 = [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]]\n | manageryears14 = 2011     | managerclubs14 = [[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]]\n | manageryears15 = 2012     | managerclubs15 = Genoa\n | manageryears16 = 2013     | managerclubs16 = [[U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo|Palermo]]\n | manageryears17 = 2014     | managerclubs17 = [[U.S. Sassuolo Calcio|Sassuolo]]\n}}\n'''Alberto Malesani''' ({{IPA-it|al\u02c8b\u025brto male\u02c8za\u02d0ni}}; born 5 June 1954) is an Italian [[association football]] [[Association football manager|manager]] and former [[Association football|footballer]]. As a manager, he is mostly remembered for his successful spell with [[Parma F.C.|Parma]] during the late 90s, where he won the [[Coppa Italia]], the [[UEFA Cup]], and the [[Supercoppa Italiana]].\n\n==Career==\n===Early career and breakthrough at Chievo===\n[[Image:Malesani.jpg|thumb|A young Malesani during his first stint as Chievo head coach]]\nMalesani career as player was mostly spent on a [[Verona|Veronese]] amateur team Audace S. Michele, where he obtained a promotion from [[Serie D]] to [[Serie C]] in 1976\u201377, appearing fourteen times on that season.<ref>{{in lang|it}} [http://www.hellastory.net/pages/scheda.cfm?id=7D590D79-4854-12EA-BD663F99594DEB70 HELLASTORY.net | La Scheda di Alberto Malesani<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He retired from playing football at the age of 24, and worked at [[Canon (company)|Canon]] in [[Amsterdam]], where he studied the [[Ajax Amsterdam]] [[total football]] training methods.<ref>[http://www.tifonet.it/fiore/malesani/bio.htm Alberto Malesani \u2013 l'antipersonaggio (la biografia)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> His passion for coaching was so great, that on his honeymoon, he decided to go to [[Barcelona]] in order to watch [[Johan Cruijff]]'s coaching sessions at [[Barcelona FC]].\n \nMalesani left his job at Canon in 1990 order to pursue a coaching career at [[Serie C1]] team [[A.C. ChievoVerona|Chievo]] for the ''Allievi'' youth squad. In 1991, he is assistant of head coach [[Carlo De Angelis]] in the first team, and in 1993 he becomes head coach himself. His first season as head coach ended in a historical promotion to [[Serie B]] for then-unknown Chievo.\n\n===Fiorentina, Parma and UEFA Cup triumph===\nMalesani left Chievo in 1997, after three impressive Serie B seasons and a narrowly missed promotion in the Serie A league in order to become [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]]'s boss, in what was his first stint in the Italian top flight.\n\nA good Fiorentina season convinced [[Parma F.C.|Parma]] to appoint Malesani as new head coach in 1998, where he won a [[Coppa Italia]], a [[UEFA Cup]], an [[Italian Super Cup]] and obtained two fourth places before being sacked during the [[2000\u201301 Serie A|2000\u201301 season]].<ref name=auction>{{cite web|url=http://gazzettaworld.gazzetta.it/off-the-ball/malesani-bid-uefa-cup-parma/?refresh_ce-cp|title=Malesani bids for UEFA Cup in Parma auction|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|author1=Sumeet Paul|date=7 October 2015|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/63457/when-parma-ruled-europe|title=When Parma ruled Europe|publisher=Football Italia|author1=Dave Taylor|date=5 March 2015|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===From Verona to Panathinaikos and Udinese===\nAfter losing his job at Parma, Malesani then coached [[Hellas Verona F.C.|Verona]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hellasverona.it/news.php?id=473|title=E' UFFICIALE, ALBERTO MALESANI SARA' L'ALLENATORE DELL'HELLAS VERONA ANCHE NELLA STAGIONE 2002/2003|date=8 February 2002|accessdate=25 April 2014|publisher=Hellas Verona FC|language=Italian}}</ref> and [[Modena F.C.|Modena]], failing to save the clubs from relegation in both cases; successively he moved abroad to coach [[Greece|Greek]] side [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]]. Panathinaikos remains the club with the highest percentage of wins in Malesani's career to date (60%).\n\nMalesani was appointed coach of [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]] in January 2007, as replacement for [[Giovanni Galeone]]. He led his side to a not particularly impressive tenth place in the [[Serie A 2006-07]] final table, only seven points far from relegation, being not confirmed for the following season. On 27 November 2007 he was unveiled as [[Empoli F.C.|Empoli]]'s new head coach, replacing [[Luigi Cagni]].<ref name=\"cagni_sacked\">{{cite news|url=http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/nov26p.html |date=26 November 2007 |accessdate=27 November 2007 |publisher=Football Italia |title=Empoli axe Cagni |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071128121509/http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/nov26p.html |archivedate=28 November 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was axed on 31 March 2008 following a 2\u20130 home defeat to [[U.C. Sampdoria]] which left Empoli down in last place in the league table.<ref name=\"malesani_sacked\">{{cite news |title=L'Empoli licenzia Malesani. In panchina torna Cagni|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Squadre/Empoli/Primo_Piano/2008/03_Marzo/31/malesani.shtml |publisher= La Gazzetta dello Sport |date= 31 March 2008 |accessdate=31 March 2008 |language=Italian}}</ref>\n\n===From Siena to Bologna===\nOn 23 November 2009 he was appointed as the new head coach of [[A.C. Siena|Siena]], replacing [[Marco Baroni]].<ref name=\"malesani_siena\">{{cite news |url=http://www.acsiena.it/comunicatidetail.php3?id=8099|language=Italian |publisher=AC Siena |accessdate=23 November 2009 |date=23 November 2009 |title=Raggiunto l'accordo con Alberto Malesani}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> On 21 May 2010 was released by Siena.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.acsiena.it/dettaglionews_3.php?id=8433|title=SportReggio {{!}} Recensioni, Prezzi, Classifiche e News|website=SportReggio|language=it-IT|access-date=2018-09-15}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 September 2010 he signed a one-year contract for [[Bologna F.C.|Bologna]].<ref>[https://archive.is/20100905064049/http://www.bolognafc.it/it/news/pagine/9274/Malesani-%E2%80%9CFinalmente-sulla-panchina-del-Bologna%E2%80%9D.html Malesani: \u201cFinalmente sulla panchina del Bologna\u201d]</ref>\nAfter a successful season which saw his club finish in 16th place, six points clear of relegation, despite a three-point deduction for tax problems and running feuds over the club's ownership, Malesani was replaced by [[Pierpaolo Bisoli]] on 26 May 2011.<ref>[http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/26052011/58/serie-bologna-dump-malesani-bisoli.html Serie A - Bologna dump Malesani for Bisoli]</ref>\n\n===Genoa===\nOn 19 June 2011 [[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]] officially announced that Malesani would be the new first team head coach.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.genoacfc.it/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=12228&Itemid=31|title=ALBERTO MALESANI NUOVO ALLENATORE |date=19 June 2011|accessdate=19 June 2011|publisher=Genoa C.F.C. |language=Italian}}</ref> However, after Genoa was defeated 6-1 by Napoli, Malesani was fired.<ref>[http://www.chron.com/sports/article/Genoa-fires-coach-Malesani-hires-Marino-2420033.php]</ref> He returned at Genoa on 2 April 2012, taking over from [[Pasquale Marino]] who had previously replaced him only to be sacked a few months later.<ref name=\"malesani_back\">{{cite news|url=http://www.genoacfc.it/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14199&Itemid=31 |title=COMUNICATO STAMPA |date=2 April 2012|accessdate=3 April 2012|work=Genoa CFC}}</ref> His second stint as Genoa boss lasted however only twenty days, as he was sacked once again on 22 April after a 1\u20134 home loss to [[A.C. Siena|Siena]] that left Genoa one point shy of relegation, and led to massive protests from Genoa fans during the game.<ref name=\"decanio_genoa\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cittadigenova.com/Genova/Sport/Incubo-Genoa-Malesani-nuovamente-50639.aspx |title=Incubo Genoa/ Malesani nuovamente esonerato. Squadra a Gigi De Canio |date=22 April 2012 |accessdate=22 April 2012 |work=Citt\u00e0 di Genova |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407083252/http://www.cittadigenova.com/Genova/Sport/Incubo-Genoa-Malesani-nuovamente-50639.aspx |archivedate=7 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Palermo===\nOn 5 February 2013, Malesani was appointed as the manager of [[U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo|Palermo]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://football-italia.net/30395/official-malesani-joins-palermo|title=Official: Malesani joins Palermo {{!}} Football Italia|website=football-italia.net|access-date=2018-09-15}}</ref>\n\nHowever, after three matches in charge, on 24 February 2013 Malesani was relieved from his duties as the manager.<ref name=\"malesani-sacked-palermo\">{{cite news |publisher=US Citt\u00e0 di Palermo |language=Italian |accessdate=26 February 2013 |date=24 February 2013 |url=http://palermocalcio.it/it/1213/news/scheda.php?id=28121 |title=ESONERATO MALESANI, RICHIAMATO GASPERINI |trans-title=MALESANI SACKED, GASPERINI RECALLED |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130227012556/http://palermocalcio.it/it/1213/news/scheda.php?id=28121 |archive-date=27 February 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Sassuolo===\nOn 29 January 2014, it was announced Malesani has agreed to take over as new manager of the top-flight team [[U.S. Sassuolo Calcio|Sassuolo]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Malesani tasked with reviving Sassuolo fortunes|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=ita/news/newsid=2048399.html |publisher= UEFA.com |date= 29 January 2014 |accessdate=8 February 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|9 March 2014}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n!rowspan=2! width=100|Team\n!rowspan=2! width=50|Nat\n!rowspan=2! width=90|From\n!rowspan=2! width=90|To\n!colspan=8|Record\n|-\n!width=30|G\n!width=30|W\n!width=30|D\n!width=30|L\n!width=50|Win %\n!width=40|GF\n!width=40|GA\n!width=40|+/-\n|-\n|align=left|[[A.C. ChievoVerona|Chievo]]\n|{{flagicon|Italy}}\n|align=left|1 June 1993{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n|align=left|30 June 1997\n| 155 || 52 || 66 || 37 || {{#expr: 52/155 * 100 round 2}} ||170||140||+30\n|-\n|align=left|[[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]]\n|{{flagicon|Italy}}\n|align=left|1 July 1997{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n|align=left|30 June 1998{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n| 40 || 18 || 15 || 7 || {{#expr: 18/40 * 100 round 2}} ||74||41||+33\n|-\n|align=left|[[Parma F.C.|Parma]]\n|{{flagicon|Italy}}\n|align=left|1 July 1998{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n|align=left|8 January 2001{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n| 123 || 62 || 33 || 28 || {{#expr: 62/123 * 100 round 2}} ||211||125||+86\n|-\n|align=left|[[Hellas Verona F.C.|Verona]]\n|{{flagicon|Italy}}\n|align=left|4 July 2001{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n|align=left|10 June 2003{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n| 77 || 23 || 23 || 31 || {{#expr: 23/77 * 100 round 2}} ||88||101||\u221213\n|-\n|align=left|[[Modena F.C.|Modena]]\n|{{flagicon|Italy}}\n|align=left|10 June 2003{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n|align=left|22 March 2004{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n| 30 || 6 || 10 || 14 || {{#expr: 6/30 * 100 round 2}} ||25||39||\u221214\n|-\n|align=left|[[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]]\n|{{flagicon|Greece}}\n|align=left|