{"title_page": "Zoom Video Communications", "text_new": "{{short description|American video communications company}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Zoom Video Communications, Inc.\n| logo                = Zoom Communications Logo.svg\n| type                = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as           = {{nowrap|{{NASDAQ|ZM}} (Class A)}}\n| foundation          = {{start date and age|2011\n}}\n| founder             = [[Eric Yuan]]\n| location_city       = {{Nowrap|[[San Jose, California]], U.S.}}\n| key_people          = Eric Yuan, founder and CEO\n| services            = Zoom Meetings<br>Zoom Premium Audio<br>Zoom Business IM<br>Zoom Video Webinar<br>Zoom Rooms<br>Zoom H.323/SIP Connector<br>Zoom Developer Platform\n| num_employees       = 1,958\n| num_employees_year  = 2019\n| website             = {{Official URL}}\n}}\n[[File:DenverZoomAdvertizement.jpg|thumb|Zoom advertisement at [[Denver International Airport]]]]\n\n'''Zoom Video Communications''' is an American remote conferencing services company headquartered in [[San Jose, California]]. It provides a remote conferencing service that combines [[Videotelephony|video conferencing]], online meetings, chat, and mobile collaboration.<ref name=\"ume\">{{cite web|url=http://www.telepresenceoptions.com/2013/01/zooms_full_featured_ume_videoc/|title=Zoom's Full Featured UME Videoconferencing Platform Exceeds Expectations|publisher=Telepresence Options|date=27 January 2013|author=Maldow, David S.}}</ref>\n\nZoom's namesake software is among the most popular remote meeting solutions in many countries. It is noted for its reliability and ease of use, especially when compared to competitors.<ref name=\"Novet 2020\">{{cite web | last=Novet | first=Jordan | title=Why Zoom has become the darling of remote workers during the COVID-19 crisis | website=CNBC | date=2020-03-21 | url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/21/why-zoom-has-become-darling-of-remote-workers-amid-covid-19-outbreak.html | access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Zoom has faced significant controversy due to a number of [[Vulnerability (computing)|security vulnerabilities]] found in its software, as well as allegations during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|recent coronavirus pandemic]] of poor [[Information privacy|privacy]] and [[Computer security|security]] practices.<ref name=\"Morrison 2020\">{{cite web | last=Morrison | first=Sara | title=Zoom responds to its privacy (and porn) problems | website=Vox | date=2020-03-31 | url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/31/21201019/zoom-coronavirus-privacy-hacks | access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nZoom was founded in 2011 by [[Eric Yuan]], a lead engineer from [[Cisco Systems]] and its collaboration business unit [[Cisco Webex|WebEx]].<ref name=ume /> The service started in January 2013, and by May 2013 it claimed one million participants.<ref name=\"tmcnet1mil\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tmcnet.com/topics/articles/2013/05/23/339279-zoom-video-communications-reaches-1-million-participants.htm |title=Zoom Video Communications Reaches 1 Million Participants |publisher=TMCnet |date=23 May 2013 |author=Pleasant, Robbie}}</ref> During the first year of its release, Zoom established partnerships with [[Business-to-business|B2B]] collaboration software providers, such as [[Redbooth]] (then Teambox),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/06/18/teambox-adds-high-definition-video-conferencing-market-looks-for-deeper-collaboration/ |publisher=[[TechCrunch]] |title=Teambox Adds High-Definition Video Conferencing, Market Looks for Deeper Collaboration |date=18 June 2013}}</ref> and also created a program named \"Works with Zoom\", which established partnerships with multiple hardware and software vendors such as [[Logitech]], Vaddio,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hdproguide.com/vaddio-and-zoom-video-communications-partner-to-bring-collaboration-to-the-enterprise/ |title=Vaddio and Zoom Video Communications Partner to Bring Collaboration to The Enterprise |publisher=HD Pro Guide |date=25 July 2013 |accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref> and [[InFocus]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://conferencing.tmcnet.com/topics/conferencing/articles/347006-zoom-launches-program-with-top-communications-tech-companies.htm |publisher=[[TMCnet]] |title=Zoom Launches Program with Top Communications Tech Companies |date=25 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.enterprisenetworkingplanet.com/unified_communications/zoom-beefs-up-video-conferencing-strategy-with-new-partners.html |title=Zoom Beefs Up Video Conferencing Strategy with New Partners |publisher=Enterprise Networking Planet |date=29 July 2013 |accessdate=11 February 2015 |author=Chao, Jude}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20130723005656/en/Zoom-Video-Communications-Partners-Industry-Leading-Technology-Providers |title=Zoom Video Communications Partners with Industry-Leading Technology Providers |publisher=[[Business Wire]] |date=23 July 2013 |accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref> \n\nBy June 2014, Zoom had 10 million users.<ref name=\"10million\">{{cite web |url=http://eir.dell.com:80/zoomed-10-million-participants/ |title=How We Zoomed to 10 Million Participants |publisher=Dell|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727223834/http://eir.dell.com:80/zoomed-10-million-participants/ |archive-date=July 27, 2014 }}</ref> In February 2015, the number of participants utilizing Zoom Video Communication's chief product, Zoom Meetings, reached 40 million individuals, with 65,000 organizations subscribed. The company had hosted a total of 1 billion meeting minutes since it was established.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.marketwired.com/press-release/zoom-raises-30m-in-series-c-funding-led-by-emergence-capital-1988574.htm |title=Zoom Raises $30M in Series C Funding Led by Emergence Capital |publisher=Market Wired}}</ref>\n\nOn February 4, 2015, Zoom Video Communications received [[US$]]30 million in [[Venture round|Series C]] funding. Participants in this funding round include Emergence Capital, Horizons Ventures ([[Li Ka-shing]]), [[Qualcomm Ventures]], [[Jerry Yang]], and [[Patrick Soon-Shiong]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2015/02/04/fast-growing-zoom-raises-30-million-for-online-video-conferencing/ |title=Fast-Growing Zoom Raises $30 Million for Online Video Conferencing |publisher=Wall Street Journal |date=4 February 2015 |author=Gage, Deborah}}</ref> In November 2015, former president of [[RingCentral]] David Berman was named president of Zoom Video Communications, and the founder and [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of [[Veeva Systems]], [[Peter Gassner]], joined Zoom's [[board of directors]].<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.marketwired.com/press-release/zoom-names-new-president-david-berman-and-board-member-peter-gassner-2069595.htm |title=Zoom Names New President David Berman and Board Member Peter Gassner |publisher=MarketWired |date=3 November 2015 |accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Zoom had officially entered the [[Unicorn (finance)|unicorn]] club (US$1 [[billion]] valuation) and attracted US$100 million in Series D funding from [[Sequoia Capital]] at a billion dollar valuation. \n\nIn September 2017, Zoom hosted Zoomtopia 2017, Zoom's first annual user conference. Zoom announced a series of new products and partnerships, including Zoom's Partnership with Meta to integrate Zoom with [[Augmented Reality]], integration with Slack and Workplace by Facebook, and first steps towards an artificial intelligence speech-to-text converter.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/09/26/zoom-brings-a-dash-of-augmented-reality-and-artificial-intelligence-to-meetings-in-latest-release/ |title=Zoom brings a dash of augmented reality and artificial intelligence to meetings in latest&nbsp;release |last=Miller |first=Ron |work=TechCrunch |access-date=2017-11-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Zoom filed to go public on the [[NASDAQ]];<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/03/22/zoom-a-profitable-unicorn-files-to-go-public/ |title=Zoom, a profitable unicorn, files to go public |last=Clark |first=Kate |date=2019-03-22 |website=TechCrunch |language=en-US |archive-url= |archive-date= |access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref> on April 18, 2019, the company went public, with shares up more than 72%, with an [[Initial public offering]] of US$36 a share.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/18/tech/zoom-ipo-video-conference/index.html |title=Zoom nearly reaches $16 billion in value after first day of trading |last=Business |first=Ahiza Garcia, Sara O'Brien and Jordan Valinsky |date=2019-04-18 |website=CNN |archive-url= |archive-date= |access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref> The company was valued at just under US$16 billion by the end of its IPO.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Use during the COVID-19 pandemic ===\n{{seealso|Teleconferencing in the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\nIn 2020, usage of Zoom rose 67% from the start of the year to mid-March as schools and companies adopted the platform for [[Telecommuting|remote work]] in response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2020/03/14/zoom-is-helping-schools-closing-due-coronavirus-fo.aspx |title=Zoom Is Helping Schools Closing Due to Coronavirus -- for Free |last=Vena |first=Danny |date=2020-03-14 |website=The Motley Fool |language=en |access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> Since the pandemic intensified, thousands of educational institutions switched to online classes using Zoom.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Mervosh |first=Sarah |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/us/coronavirus-closings.html |title=Colleges and Universities Cancel Classes and Move Online Amid Coronavirus Fears |date=2020-03-10 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-03-26 |last2=Swales |first2=Vanessa |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2020/03/20/schooling-rapidly-moves-online-across-country-concerns-rise-about-student-data-privacy/ |title=As schooling rapidly moves online across the country, concerns rise about student data privacy |last=Strauss |first=Valerie |date=March 20, 2020 |website=The Washington post |url-status=live |archive-url= |archive-date= |access-date=}}</ref> The company offered its services to [[K\u201312]] schools free of charge in many countries.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alexkonrad/2020/03/13/zoom-video-coronavirus-eric-yuan-schools/ |title=Exclusive: Zoom CEO Eric Yuan Is Giving K-12 Schools His Videoconferencing Tools For Free |last=Konrad |first=Alex |website=Forbes |language=en |access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> In one day, the Zoom app was downloaded 343,000 times with about 18% of those downloads originating in the United States.<ref name=\":5\" /> Zoom gained over 2.22 million users in the first months of 2020\u2014more users than it amassed in the entirety of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/26/zoom-has-added-more-users-so-far-this-year-than-in-2019-bernstein.html |title=Zoom has added more videoconferencing users this year than in all of 2019 thanks to coronavirus, Bernstein says |last=Novet |first=Jordan |date=2020-02-26 |website=CNBC |language=en |access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Consequently, by March 2020, Zoom shares increased to US$160.98 per share, a 263% increase from initial share prices when it first went public.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/zoom-stock-price-surged-coronavirus-pandemic-video-work-from-home-2020-3-1029023594 |title=Zoom Video has seen its stock spike more than 100% since January as coronavirus pushes millions to work from home (ZM) |last=Reinicke |first=Carmen |date=23 March 2020 |website=markets.businessinsider.com |url-status=live |archive-url= |archive-date= |access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>  The company reported daily average users rose from about 10 million in December 2019 to about 200 million in March 2020.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2020/04/03/826129520/a-must-for-millions-zoom-has-a-dark-side-and-an-fbi-warning A Must For Millions, Zoom Has A Dark Side \u2014 And An FBI Warning]</ref>\n\nZoom also became a popular social platform over the course of the pandemic.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news |last=Lorenz |first=Taylor |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/style/zoom-parties-coronavirus-memes.html |title=We Live in Zoom Now |date=2020-03-17 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-03-26 |last2=Griffith |first2=Erin |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |last3=Isaac |first3=Mike}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/23/ok-zoomer-zoom-worlds-new-favourite-social-network-12443418/ |title=Ok Zoomer: Why Zoom is the world's new favourite social network |last=Parsons |first=Jeff |date=2020-03-23 |website=Metro |language=en |url-status=live |archive-url= |archive-date= |access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> [[Generation Z|Gen Z]] and [[Millennials]]{{dubious|date=April 2020}}<!-- some people outside these generations have no doubt also done so; arguably, this claim is ageist --> have connected with each other through events such as \"Zoom Blind Dates\", and \"Zoom Recess\".<ref name=\":4\" /> Zoom as a company has developed into an [[Internet meme]] and students at a number of colleges and universities have spread memes about its use as \"Zoom University\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Wagner |first=James |url=https://www.nytimes.com/live/2020/coronavirus-update-03-13 |title=How Coronavirus Is Changing Our Daily Lives: Latest Updates |date=2020-03-14 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-03-14 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Lorenz |first= Taylor |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/style/zoom-parties-coronavirus-memes.html |title=We Live in Zoom Now |date=March 17, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live |last2=Griffith |first2=Erin |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |last3=Isaac |first3=Mike}}</ref> Zoom has also gained popularity amongst older users and families separated by ongoing [[social distancing]] guidelines and mandates. These virtual social gatherings are often referred to as \"Zoom Parties\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/how-to-throw-zoom-party-custom-background-friends-family-2020-3 |title=How to throw a perfect Zoom party with your friends and family |last=Tenbarge |first=Kat |website=Business Insider |access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> \n\nWith the rise of videoconferencing, incidents of \"[[Zoombombing|{{Anchor|Zoombombing}}Zoombombing]]\", the practice of participants unexpectedly appearing in conferences and sending [[pornography]] or other offensive material to other attendees, have occurred,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2020/03/25/zoombombing-disrupts-online-classes-university-southern-california/ |title='Zoombombing' disrupts online classes at University of Southern California |website=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-03-25/zoombombing-usc-classes-interrupted-racist-remarks |title=USC, school districts getting 'Zoom-bombed' with racist taunts, porn as they transition to online meetings |date=March 25, 2020 |website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2020/03/17/zoombombing/ |title=Beware of 'ZoomBombing:' screensharing filth to video calls |date=March 18, 2020 |website=TechCrunch}}</ref> causing some organizations to abandon the use of Zoom.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor Lorenz |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/20/style/zoombombing-zoom-trolling.html |title='Zoombombing': When Video Conferences Go Wrong |work=The New York Times |accessdate=27 March 2020 |language=en |quote=On Tuesday, Chipotle was forced to end a public Zoom chat that the brand had co-hosted with the musician Lauv after one participant began broadcasting pornography to hundreds of attendees [...] \u201cWe did encounter an unwanted \u2018Zoombomb\u2019 during one of our sessions so we moved our latest performances to a different platform.\u201d}}</ref> To combat this, Zoom introduced a new feature which requires users to input a password as they join a meeting.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Akolawala |first1=Tasneem |title=Zoom Meeting App: New Security Features Introduced to Prevent Zoombombing, Thousands Saved Videos Reportedly Leak Online |url=https://gadgets.ndtv.com/apps/news/zoom-meeting-app-password-waiting-room-security-features-zoombombing-videos-leak-online-2206139 |website=Gadgets 360 |publisher=NDTV |accessdate=8 April 2020 |date=4 April 2020}}</ref> Additionally, they published a guide to reduce the chances of such incidents.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://blog.zoom.us/wordpress/2020/03/20/keep-the-party-crashers-from-crashing-your-zoom-event/ |title=How to Keep the Party Crashers from Crashing Your Zoom Event |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nZoom's data security and privacy practices have also come under increased scrutiny.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-52115434|title=Zoom under increased scrutiny as popularity soars|date=2020-04-01|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-GB}}</ref> Consequently, Zoom's CEO released a statement apologizing for the security issues.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/02/tech/zoom-ceo-apology-privacy/index.html|title=Zoom CEO apologizes for having 'fallen short' on privacy and security|last=Iyengar|first=Rishi|date=2 April 2020|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Some of the issues were a result of Zoom having been designed for \"large institutions with full IT support.\"<ref name=\":7\"/> To combat these issues, Zoom has said it will focus on data privacy and issue a transparency report.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Alex |last1=Hern |accessdate=2020-04-05|title=Zoom says engineers will focus on security and safety issues|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/apr/02/zoom-says-engineers-will-focus-on-security-and-safety-issues|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2 April 2020|issn=0261-3077|via=theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2020-04-05|title=SMBlog -- 2 April 2020|url=https://www.cs.columbia.edu/~smb/blog/2020-04/2020-04-02.html|author=[[Steven M. Bellovin]]}}</ref>\n\n== Products ==\nZoom provides video conferencing for up to 100 participants, with a 40-minute time limit. Beyond this, paid subscriptions are available to allow more participants, increase the time limit, and obtain more advanced features. Zoom claims that its software is compliant with [[FedRAMP]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://convergentav.net/2018/07/10/zoom-achieves-fedramp-in-process-milestone/|title=Zoom Achieves FedRAMP \"In Process\" Milestone|date=2018-07-10|website=Convergent|language=en|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref> [[Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act|HIPAA]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hipaajournal.com/zoom-hipaa-compliant/|title=Is Zoom a HIPAA Compliant Video and Web Conferencing Platform?|date=2018-02-19|website=HIPAA Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref> [[Personal Information Protection and Electronic Documents Act|PIPEDA]] and [[Personal Health Information Protection Act|PHIPA]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bitpipe.com/detail/RES/1548948281_430.html|title=Build patient engagement with compliant video conferencing|website=bitpipe.com|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref> and the [[General Data Protection Regulation|GDPR]], however these claims cannot be verified by security researchers around the world as the applications are [[Proprietary software|closed source]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/360000126326-Official-Statement-EU-GDPR-Compliance|title=Official Statement: EU GDPR Compliance|website=Zoom Help Center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> Zoom has received various industry recognitions for its products.<ref>{{cite web |title=Awards Archives |url=https://blog.zoom.us/wordpress/category/awards/ |website=Zoom blog |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nInitially, Zoom could host conferences with up to 15 video participants,<ref name=\"15participants\">{{cite web | url=https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10000872396390444443504577603383238616426?mg=reno64-wsj&url=http%3A%2F%2Fonline.wsj.com%2Farticle%2FSB10000872396390444443504577603383238616426.html | title=A Chance To Call 15 Friends To Video Chat In High Def | publisher=Wall Street Journal | date=21 August 2012 | author=[[Walt Mossberg|Mossberg, Walter S.]]}}</ref> increased to 25 in January 2013, to 100 with version 2.5 in October 2015,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.eweek.com/networking/zoom-doubles-capacity-of-video-conferencing-service-to-50.html | title=Zoom Doubles Capacity of Video Conferencing Service to 50 | publisher=eWeek | date=2 October 2015 | accessdate=19 November 2015 | author=Burt, Jeffrey}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://zoom.us/pricing|title=Video Conferencing, Web Conferencing, Webinars, Screen Sharing|website=Zoom Video|language=en-US|access-date=2017-11-29}}</ref> and later to 1,000 for business customers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/skype-vs-zoom-which-video-chat-app-is-best-for-working-from-home/|title=Skype vs. Zoom: Which video chat app is best for working from home?|first=Shelby|last=Brown|date=10 March 2020|work=CNET|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>  Between 2015 and mid-2016, Zoom Video Communications announced native support for [[Skype for Business]] and integration with [[Slack (software)|Slack]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.zoom.us/wordpress/2015/08/13/zoom-slack-integration/|title=Announcement: Zoom Slack Integration|last=|first=|date=13 August 2015|website=Zoom Blog|publisher=|access-date=8 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msn.com/en-us/money/other/zoom-announces-native-skype-for-business-interoperability/ar-BBr50fP|title=Zoom Announces Native Skype for Business Interoperability|website=msn.com|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, Zoom announced integration of Zoom video conferencing with [[Salesforce]]'s [[customer relationship management]] platform, allowing salespeople to initiate such conferences with their [[sales lead]]s without leaving the application.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tmcnet.com/channels/ip-phones/articles/409907-zoom-announces-salesforce-integration.htm|title=Zoom Announces Salesforce Integration|author=Delony, David|date=15 September 2015|publisher=TMCnet|accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref> In April 2017, Zoom launched Telehealth, a scalable [[telehealth]] product allowing doctors to remotely visit their patients through video for consultation.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://conferencing.tmcnet.com/topics/conferencing/articles/431502-zoom-introduces-new-telehealth-solution.htm |title=Zoom Introduces New Telehealth Solution |last=Young |first=Alicia |date=24 April 2017 |work=TMCnet |access-date=7 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.globenewswire.com/news-release/2017/04/20/1311124/0/en/Zoom-Launches-Industry-s-First-Scalable-Cloud-Based-Video-Telehealth-Solution.html|title=Zoom Launches Industry's First Scalable Cloud-Based Video Telehealth Solution|first=Zoom Video Communications|last=Inc|date=April 20, 2017|website=GlobeNewswire News Room}}</ref> In May 2017, Zoom announced a partnership with [[Polycom]] that integrated Zoom's video meetings into Polycom's conferencing systems, enabling features such as multiple screen and device meetings, HD and wireless screen sharing, and calendar integration with [[Microsoft Outlook]], [[Google Calendar]], and [[iCal]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/polycom-zoom-forge-video-conferencing-collaboration-pact/|title=Polycom, Zoom forge video conferencing, collaboration pact {{!}} ZDNet|last=Dignan|first=Larry|date=2017-05-25|work=ZDNet|access-date=2017-11-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n\n===Privacy===\nZoom has been criticized for its [[Digital hoarding|data hoarding]] practices,<ref>{{cite web |last1=St. John |first1=Allen |title=Zoom Calls Aren't as Private as You May Think. Here's What You Should Know. |url=https://www.consumerreports.org/video-conferencing-services/zoom-teleconferencing-privacy-concerns/ |website=Consumer Reports |accessdate=26 March 2020 |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> which include its collection and storage of \"the content contained in cloud recordings, and instant messages, files, whiteboards\" as well as its enabling employers to monitor workers remotely;<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kate O'Flaherty |title=Zoom's A Lifeline During COVID-19: This Is Why It's Also A Privacy Risk |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kateoflahertyuk/2020/03/25/zooms-a-lifeline-during-covid-19-this-is-why-its-also-a-privacy-risk/#508f8eb428ba |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=Forbes |date=25 March 2020 |language=en |quote=collects and stores personal data and shares it with third parties such as advertisers. But Zoom\u2019s policy also covers what it labels \u201ccustomer content,\u201d or \"the content contained in cloud recordings, and instant messages, files, whiteboards ... shared while using the service.\"  This includes videos, transcripts that can be generated automatically, documents shared on screen, and the names of everyone on a call.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Morse |first1=Jack |title=Zoom is a work-from-home privacy disaster waiting to happen |url=https://mashable.com/article/zoom-conference-call-work-from-home-privacy-concerns/ |website=Mashable |accessdate=26 March 2020 |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> the [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]] warned that administrators can join any call at any time \"without in-the-moment consent or warning for the attendees of the call.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2020/03/what-you-should-know-about-online-tools-during-covid-19-crisis|title=What You Should Know About Online Tools During the COVID-19 Crisis|first=Lindsay|last=Oliver|date=March 19, 2020|website=Electronic Frontier Foundation}}</ref>   During signup for a Zoom free account, Zoom requires users to permit it to identify users with their personal information on Google and also offers to permanently delete their Google contacts.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nWidespread use of Zoom for online education during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|novel coronavirus pandemic]] increased concerns regarding students' data privacy and, in particular, their [[Personal data|personally identifiable information]].<ref name=\":2\" /> According to the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]], students\u2019 IP addresses, browsing history, academic progress, and biometric data may be at risk during the use of similar online learning services.<ref name=\":2\" /> Privacy experts are also concerned that the use of Zoom by schools and universities may raise issues regarding unauthorized surveillance of students and possible violations of students\u2019 rights under the [[Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act]] (FERPA).<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2020/03/25/pivot-online-raises-concerns-ferpa-surveillance|title=Pivot to online raises concerns for FERPA, surveillance|last=St. Amour|first=Madeline|date=|website=insidehighered.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> The company claims that the video services are FERPA-compliant, and also claims that it collects and stores user data only to \"provide technical and operational support\".<ref name=\":3\" />  \n\nThe company's [[iOS]] app was found to be sending device analytics data to Facebook on startup, regardless of whether a Facebook account was being used with the service, and without mentioning it to the user.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/k7e599/zoom-ios-app-sends-data-to-facebook-even-if-you-dont-have-a-facebook-account|title=Zoom iOS App Sends Data to Facebook Even if You Don't Have a Facebook Account|last=Cox|first=Joseph|date=2020-03-26|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> On March 27, Zoom stated that it had been \"recently made aware that the Facebook [[Software development kit|SDK]] was collecting unnecessary device data\", and that it had patched the app to remove the SDK (which was primarily used for [[social login]] support) in order to address these concerns. The company stated that the SDK was only collecting information on the user's device specifications (such as model names and operating system versions), and was not collecting personal information.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/z3b745/zoom-removes-code-that-sends-data-to-facebook|title=Zoom Removes Code That Sends Data to Facebook|last=Cox|first=Joseph|date=2020-03-27|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> In April 2020, The [[New York Times]] reported that a data-mining feature on Zoom automatically sent user names and email addresses to [[LinkedIn]] via a tool meant to match user profiles, allowing some participants to surreptitiously access LinkedIn profile data about other users.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Aaron Krolik|last2=Natasha Singer|title=A Feature on Zoom Secretly Displayed Data From People's LinkedIn Profiles|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/02/technology/zoom-linkedin-data.html|accessdate=3 April 2020|work=[[The New York Times]]|language=en|quote=as high school students in Colorado signed in to a mandatory video meeting for a class, Zoom readied the full names and email addresses of at least six students \u2014 and their teacher \u2014 for possible use by its LinkedIn profile-matching tool, according to a Times analysis of the data traffic that Zoom sent to a student\u2019s account.}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Zoom was sued in U.S. Federal Court for illegally disclosing personal data to third parties including Facebook. According to the suit, Zoom's privacy policy does not explain to users that its app contains code that discloses information to Facebook and potentially other third parties. The company's \"wholly inadequate program design and security measures have resulted, and will continue to result, in unauthorized disclosure of its users\u2019 personal information,\" according to the complaint.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rosenblatt |first1=Joel |title=Zoom Sued for Allegedly Illegally Disclosing Personal Data |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-31/zoom-sued-for-allegedly-illegally-disclosing-personal-data |website=Bloomberg}}</ref> The same month, the [[New York State Attorney General]], [[Letitia James]] launched an inquiry into Zoom's privacy and security practices.<ref name=\"nytimes-hakim-singer\"/><ref name=\"ft-murphy\"/>\n\n=== Security ===\n{{further|Zoombombing}}\n\nZoom claims to use [[TLS 1.2]] with [[Advanced Encryption Standard]] 256-bit (AES-256) for the Zoom client. In details, Zoom uses TLS 1.2 with AES-256 to protect [[Signaling (telecommunications)|signaling]], and uses AES-128 to protect [[Streaming media|audio and video streams]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/201362723-Encryption-for-Meetings |title=Encryption for Meetings &ndash; Zoom Help Center |date= |website=Zoom |language=en-US |access-date=2020-04-07 }}</ref>Zoom claims to use \"[[end-to-end encryption]]\" in its marketing materials,<ref>{{Cite web|url=hhttps://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/207599823-End-To-End-Encryption-for-Chat |title=End-To-End Encryption for Chat &ndash; Zoom Help Center |date= |website=Zoom |language=en-US |access-date=2020-04-07 }}</ref> but later clarified it meant \"from Zoom end point to Zoom end point\" (meaning effectively between Zoom servers and Zoom clients), which is misleading and has been described as \"dishonest\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2020/03/31/zoom-meeting-encryption/|title=Zoom Meetings Aren't End-to-End Encrypted, Despite Misleading Marketing|last=Lee|first=Micah|last2=Grauer|first2=Yael|date=2020-03-31|website=The Intercept|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31|quote=Currently, it is not possible to enable E2E encryption for Zoom video meetings. (...) When we use the phrase \u2018End to End\u2019 in our other literature, it is in reference to the connection being encrypted from Zoom end point to Zoom end point.}}</ref> [[CitizenLab|Citizenlab]] researchers also discovered that in reality a single, server-generated AES-128 key is being shared between all participants in [[Block cipher mode of operation|ECB mode]], which is deprecated due to its pattern-preserving characteristics of the ciphertext. During test calls between participants in Canada and USA the key was provisioned from servers located in mainland China where they are subject to the [[China Internet Security Law]].<ref name=\"citizenlab\">{{Cite web|url=https://citizenlab.ca/2020/04/move-fast-roll-your-own-crypto-a-quick-look-at-the-confidentiality-of-zoom-meetings/|title=Move Fast & Roll Your Own Crypto: A Quick Look at the Confidentiality of Zoom Meetings|date=2020-04-03|website=The Citizen Lab|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> \n\nIn November 2018, a security vulnerability ({{CVE|2018-15715}}) was discovered<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2018-15715 |title=CVE-2018-15715 |website=National Vulnerability Database |access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref> that allowed a remote unauthenticated attacker to spoof UDP messages from a meeting attendee or Zoom server in order to invoke functionality in the target client. This would allow the attacker to remove attendees from meetings, spoof messages from users, or hijack shared screens. Another vulnerability allowing the client unprompted access to camera and microphone was made public on April 1st, 2020, and was fixed by the evening ([https://cve.mitre.org/cgi-bin/cvename.cgi?name=CVE-2020-11470 CVE-2020-11470]).<ref>{{cite journal |title=The Zoom Privacy Backlash Is Only Getting Started |journal=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |date=Apr 1, 2020 |url=https://www.wired.com/story/zoom-backlash-zero-days/}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, security researcher Jonathan Leitschuh disclosed<ref>{{cite web |url=https://medium.com/@jonathan.leitschuh/zoom-zero-day-4-million-webcams-maybe-an-rce-just-get-them-to-visit-your-website-ac75c83f4ef5 |title=Zoom Zero Day: 4+ Million Webcams & maybe an RCE? Just get them to visit your website! |last=Leitschuh |first=Jonathan |date=2019-07-09 |website=Medium |language=en |access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref> a [[zero-day (computing)|zero-day]] vulnerability allowing any website to forcibly join a [[macOS]] user to a Zoom call, with their video camera activated, without the user's permission. In addition, attempts to uninstall the Zoom client on macOS would prompt the software to re-install automatically in the background, using a hidden web server that was set up on the machine during the first installation and remained active even after attempting to remove the client. After receiving public criticism, Zoom updated their software to remove the vulnerability and the hidden webserver, allowing complete uninstallation.<ref name=\"Anderson 2019\">{{cite web | last=Anderson | first=Tim | title=Anyone for unintended Chat Roulette? Zoom installs hidden Mac web server to allow auto-join video conferencing | website=The Register | date=2019-07-09 | url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2019/07/09/zooms_hidden_mac_web_server_allows_autojoin_conferencing_exploit/ | access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nThe increased use of Zoom during the coronavirus pandemic caused increased scrutiny of Zoom's security, including cases where Windows users' [[Credential#Information technology|credentials]] could be exposed.<ref>{{cite news |first=Dan |last=Goodin |title=Attackers can use Zoom to steal users' Windows credentials with no warning |url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2020/04/unpatched-zoom-bug-lets-attackers-steal-windows-credentials-with-no-warning/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[Ars Technica]] |date=1 April 2020 |language=en |quote=The vulnerability was first described last week by a researcher who uses the Twitter handle @_g0dmode. He wrote: \u201c#Zoom chat allows you to post links such as \\\\x.x.x.x\\xyz to attempt to capture Net-NTLM hashes if clicked by other users.}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |author=Mitch |user=_g0dmode |number=1242131019026874369 |date=2020-03-23 |title=#Zoom chat allows you to post links such as \\\\x.x.x.x\\xyz to attempt to capture Net-NTLM hashes if clicked by other users.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/zoom-lets-attackers-steal-windows-credentials-run-programs-via-unc-links/|title=Zoom Lets Attackers Steal Windows Credentials, Run Programs via UNC Links|website=BleepingComputer|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Zoom-related [[phishing]] scams also emerged, such as an increase of fake Zoom websites and links created to steal personal information.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.computerweekly.com/news/252480806/Coronavirus-Warning-over-surge-in-Zoom-security-incidents|title=Coronavirus: Warning over surge in Zoom security incidents|last=Scroxton|first=Alex|date=30 March 2020|website=ComputerWeekly.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> \"[[Zoombombing]]\", when an unwanted participant joins a meeting to cause disruption, also increased, prompting a warning from the [[FBI]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/contact-us/field-offices/boston/news/press-releases/fbi-warns-of-teleconferencing-and-online-classroom-hijacking-during-covid-19-pandemic|title=FBI Warns of Teleconferencing and Online Classroom Hijacking During COVID-19 Pandemic|date=30 March 2020|website=fbi.gov}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first1=Alex |last1=Hern |accessdate=2020-04-05|title=Trolls exploit Zoom privacy settings as app gains popularity|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/mar/27/trolls-zoom-privacy-settings-covid-19-lockdown|newspaper=The Guardian|date=27 March 2020|issn=0261-3077|via=theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, Zoom admitted that some Zoom calls were being routed through servers in mainland China. Zoom Video Communications offered an apology but only a partial explanation.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Zack |last1=Whittaker|accessdate=2020-04-05|title=Zoom admits some calls were routed through China by mistake|url=https://techcrunch.com/2020/04/03/zoom-calls-routed-china|newspaper=TechCrunch|date=4 April 2020}}</ref> In April, the New York Attorney General has issued a number of official and explicit questions about Zoom.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Jerry |last1=McNerney|accessdate=2020-04-05|title=Rep. McNerney and Colleagues Push Zoom for Answers About the Company's Privacy Practices|url=https://mcnerney.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/rep-mcnerney-and-colleagues-push-zoom-for-answers-about-the-company-s|date=3 April 2020}}</ref> Further, in April 2020, security researchers with [[Citizen_Lab|The Citizen Lab]] issued a report that concluded that Zoom features significant security and encryption weaknesses. <ref>{{cite news|first1=Bill Marczak|last1=John Scott-Railton|accessdate=2020-04-05|title= Move Fast & Roll Your Own Crypto: A Quick Look at the Confidentiality of Zoom Meetings|url=https://citizenlab.ca/2020/04/move-fast-roll-your-own-crypto-a-quick-look-at-the-confidentiality-of-zoom-meetings|newspaper=The Citizen Lab|date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn light of numerous privacy and security concerns,<ref>{{cite news|first1=Kari|last1=Paul|accessdate=2020-04-05|title='Zoom is malware': why experts worry about the video conferencing platform|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/apr/02/zoom-technology-security-coronavirus-video-conferencing|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2 April 2020|issn=0261-3077|via=theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2020-04-05|title=Is Zoom safe and can it be hacked?|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/features/zoom-safe-hack-how-secure-encryption-a9440461.html|date=2 April 2020|website=The Independent}}</ref> in March 2020 the [[New York State Attorney General]], [[Letitia James]], launched an inquiry into Zoom's privacy and security practices.<ref name=\"nytimes-hakim-singer\">{{cite news|first1=Danny|last1=Hakim|first2=Natasha|last2=Singer|accessdate=2020-04-04|title=New York Attorney General Looks Into Zoom's Privacy Practices|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/30/technology/new-york-attorney-general-zoom-privacy.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=30 March 2020|issn=0362-4331|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref name=\"ft-murphy\">{{cite web|accessdate=2020-04-05|title=Privacy concerns grow over Zoom videoconferencing platform|url=https://www.ft.com/content/bdedc70b-e559-489e-bfa0-445b9c882f7b|website=ft.com}}</ref> Following these inquiries, Zoom was banned from New York City schools by the [[New York City Department of Education]] due to security and privacy issues with the platform.<ref name=\"FastCo\">{{cite news|first1=Ainsley |last1=Harris|accessdate=2020-04-05|title=Zoom banned from New York City schools due to privacy and security flaws|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/90486586/zoom-banned-from-new-york-city-schools-due-to-privacy-and-security-flaws|newspaper=Fast Company|date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Bans===\nDue to the various privacy and security concerns, numerous organizations and government entities have banned the use of Zoom:\n\n*[[Australian Defence Force]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tim Biggs|title=Zoom says it's safe for Australian companies to use as security concerns escalate|url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/zoom-says-it-s-safe-for-australian-companies-to-use-as-security-concerns-escalate-20200406-p54hj0.html|accessdate=7 April 2020|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=7 April 2020|language=en|quote=the Australian Defence Force banning its members from using the service}}</ref>\n\n*[[Berkeley, California]] (public school use)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eastbaytimes.com/2020/04/08/zoom-bombers-disrupt-berkeley-schools/|title=Zoom bomber exposed himself to Berkeley High students, school official says|date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n*[[Canada]] (Federal government use that requires secure communications)<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2020-04-08|title=Taiwan joins Canada in banning Zoom for government video conferencing|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/taiwan-zoom-video-conference-1.5524384|website=CBC News|date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n*[[Clark County, Nevada]] (public school use)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/local/education/clark-county-schools-ban-zoom-app-over-security-concerns-1997093/|title=Clark County schools ban Zoom app over security concerns|date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> \n\n*[[German Ministry of Foreign Affairs]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/german-government-restricts-use-of-zoom-over-security-concerns-reports/a-53069274|title=German government restricts use of Zoom over security concerns - reports &#124; DW &#124; 08.04.2020|first=Deutsche|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|website=DW.COM}}</ref>\n\n*[[Google]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/google-bans-zoom-from-employee-computers-due-to-security-concerns-2020-4|title=Google has banned the Zoom app from all employee computers over 'security vulnerabilities'|first=Hugh|last=Langley|website=Business Insider}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/technology/google-bans-its-employees-from-using-zoom-over-security-concerns/ar-BB12kZKT|title=Google bans its employees from using Zoom over security concerns|website=msn.com}}</ref>\n\n*[[NASA]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Elon Musk's SpaceX bans Zoom over privacy concerns, memo shows |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/01/elon-musks-spacex-bans-zoom-over-privacy-concerns-memo-shows.html |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=CNBC |date=1 April 2020 |language=en |quote=NASA, one of SpaceX\u2019s biggest customers, also prohibits its employees from using Zoom, said Stephanie Schierholz, a spokeswoman for the U.S. space agency.}}</ref>\n\n*[[New York City]] (public school use)<ref>{{cite news|last=Harris|first1=Ainsley|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/90486586/zoom-banned-from-new-york-city-schools-due-to-privacy-and-security-flaws|title=Zoom banned from New York City schools due to privacy and security flaws|date=5 April 2020|newspaper=Fast Company|accessdate=2020-04-05|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*[[Singapore Ministry of Education]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-zoom-video-comm-privacy-singapore-idUSKCN21S0AH|title=Singapore stops teachers using Zoom app after very serious incidents|date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/moe-suspends-zoom-home-based-learning-obscene-images-12626534|title=MOE suspends use of Zoom in home-based learning following breaches involving obscene images|date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n*[[Smart Communications]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://micky.com.au/major-philippine-telco-bans-internal-use-of-zoom-cites-security-risks/|title=Major Philippine telco bans internal use of Zoom, cites security risks|date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n*[[SpaceX]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/04/02/business/02reuters-spacex-zoom-video-commn.html|title=Elon Musk's SpaceX Bans Zoom Over Privacy Concerns - Memo|date=2 April 2020|website=nytimes.com|language=en}}</ref>\n\n*[[Taiwan]] (government use)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Debby Wu|last2=Samson Ellis|title=Taiwan Bans Government Use of Zoom Over Cybersecurity Concerns|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-07/taiwan-bans-government-use-of-zoom-over-cybersecurity-concerns|accessdate=7 April 2020|work=[[Bloomberg L.P.]]|date=7 April 2020|language=en|quote=Taiwan barred all official use of Zoom, becoming one of the first governments to impose an outright ban on the popular video-conferencing app over security concerns.}}</ref> \n\n*[[United Kingdom Ministry of Defence]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/25/concern-zoom-video-conferencing-mod-bans-security-fears-12455327/|title=Concern over Zoom video conferencing after MoD bans it over security fears|date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronairus-cabinet-talks-held-on-zoom-days-after-software-was-banned-by-ministry-of-defence-11963889|title=Coronavirus: Cabinet talks held on Zoom days after software was banned by Ministry of Defence|website=Sky News}}</ref>\n\n*[[United States Senate]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/us-senate-german-government-tell-staff-not-to-use-zoom/|title=US Senate, German government tell staff not to use Zoom|date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/senate-warns-against-zoom-2020-4/|title=The US Senate reportedly advised members to stop using Zoom|date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Telecommunication}}\n{{Portal|Technology}}\n*[[List of video telecommunication services and product brands]]\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://zoom.us Official website]\n{{Finance links\n| name      = Zoom Video Communications, Inc.\n| symbol    = ZM\n| reuters   = ZM.O\n| bloomberg = ZM:US\n| sec_cik   = ZM\n| yahoo     = ZM\n| google    = ZM\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Software companies established in 2011]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies established in 2011]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2011]]\n[[Category:2011 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Software companies based in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Companies based in San Jose, California]]\n[[Category:Web conferencing]]\n[[Category:Videotelephony]]\n[[Category:2019 initial public offerings]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on NASDAQ]]\n[[Category:Software companies of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American video communications company}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Zoom Video Communications, Inc.\n| logo                = Zoom Communications Logo.svg\n| type                = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as           = {{nowrap|{{NASDAQ|ZM}} (Class A)}}\n| foundation          = {{start date and age|2011\n}}\n| founder             = [[Eric Yuan]]\n| location_city       = {{Nowrap|[[San Jose, California]], U.S.}}\n| key_people          = Eric Yuan, founder and CEO\n| services            = Zoom Meetings<br>Zoom Premium Audio<br>Zoom Business IM<br>Zoom Video Webinar<br>Zoom Rooms<br>Zoom H.323/SIP Connector<br>Zoom Developer Platform\n| num_employees       = 1,958\n| num_employees_year  = 2019\n| website             = {{Official URL}}\n}}\n[[File:DenverZoomAdvertizement.jpg|thumb|Zoom advertisement at [[Denver International Airport]]]]\n\n'''Zoom Video Communications''' is an American remote conferencing services company headquartered in [[San Jose, California]]. It provides a remote conferencing service that combines [[Videotelephony|video conferencing]], online meetings, chat, and mobile collaboration.<ref name=\"ume\">{{cite web|url=http://www.telepresenceoptions.com/2013/01/zooms_full_featured_ume_videoc/|title=Zoom's Full Featured UME Videoconferencing Platform Exceeds Expectations|publisher=Telepresence Options|date=27 January 2013|author=Maldow, David S.}}</ref>\n\nZoom's namesake software is among the most popular remote meeting solutions in many countries. It is noted for its reliability and ease of use, especially when compared to competitors.<ref name=\"Novet 2020\">{{cite web | last=Novet | first=Jordan | title=Why Zoom has become the darling of remote workers during the COVID-19 crisis | website=CNBC | date=2020-03-21 | url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/21/why-zoom-has-become-darling-of-remote-workers-amid-covid-19-outbreak.html | access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Zoom has faced significant controversy due to a number of [[Vulnerability (computing)|security vulnerabilities]] found in its software, as well as allegations during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|recent coronavirus pandemic]] of poor [[Information privacy|privacy]] and [[Computer security|security]] practices.<ref name=\"Morrison 2020\">{{cite web | last=Morrison | first=Sara | title=Zoom responds to its privacy (and porn) problems | website=Vox | date=2020-03-31 | url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/31/21201019/zoom-coronavirus-privacy-hacks | access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nZoom was founded in 2011 by [[Eric Yuan]], a lead engineer from [[Cisco Systems]] and its collaboration business unit [[Cisco Webex|WebEx]].<ref name=ume /> The service started in January 2013, and by May 2013 it claimed one million participants.<ref name=\"tmcnet1mil\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tmcnet.com/topics/articles/2013/05/23/339279-zoom-video-communications-reaches-1-million-participants.htm |title=Zoom Video Communications Reaches 1 Million Participants |publisher=TMCnet |date=23 May 2013 |author=Pleasant, Robbie}}</ref> During the first year of its release, Zoom established partnerships with [[Business-to-business|B2B]] collaboration software providers, such as [[Redbooth]] (then Teambox),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/06/18/teambox-adds-high-definition-video-conferencing-market-looks-for-deeper-collaboration/ |publisher=[[TechCrunch]] |title=Teambox Adds High-Definition Video Conferencing, Market Looks for Deeper Collaboration |date=18 June 2013}}</ref> and also created a program named \"Works with Zoom\", which established partnerships with multiple hardware and software vendors such as [[Logitech]], Vaddio,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hdproguide.com/vaddio-and-zoom-video-communications-partner-to-bring-collaboration-to-the-enterprise/ |title=Vaddio and Zoom Video Communications Partner to Bring Collaboration to The Enterprise |publisher=HD Pro Guide |date=25 July 2013 |accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref> and [[InFocus]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://conferencing.tmcnet.com/topics/conferencing/articles/347006-zoom-launches-program-with-top-communications-tech-companies.htm |publisher=[[TMCnet]] |title=Zoom Launches Program with Top Communications Tech Companies |date=25 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.enterprisenetworkingplanet.com/unified_communications/zoom-beefs-up-video-conferencing-strategy-with-new-partners.html |title=Zoom Beefs Up Video Conferencing Strategy with New Partners |publisher=Enterprise Networking Planet |date=29 July 2013 |accessdate=11 February 2015 |author=Chao, Jude}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20130723005656/en/Zoom-Video-Communications-Partners-Industry-Leading-Technology-Providers |title=Zoom Video Communications Partners with Industry-Leading Technology Providers |publisher=[[Business Wire]] |date=23 July 2013 |accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref> \n\nBy June 2014, Zoom had 10 million users.<ref name=\"10million\">{{cite web |url=http://eir.dell.com:80/zoomed-10-million-participants/ |title=How We Zoomed to 10 Million Participants |publisher=Dell|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727223834/http://eir.dell.com:80/zoomed-10-million-participants/ |archive-date=July 27, 2014 }}</ref> In February 2015, the number of participants utilizing Zoom Video Communication's chief product, Zoom Meetings, reached 40 million individuals, with 65,000 organizations subscribed. The company had hosted a total of 1 billion meeting minutes since it was established.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.marketwired.com/press-release/zoom-raises-30m-in-series-c-funding-led-by-emergence-capital-1988574.htm |title=Zoom Raises $30M in Series C Funding Led by Emergence Capital |publisher=Market Wired}}</ref>\n\nOn February 4, 2015, Zoom Video Communications received [[US$]]30 million in [[Venture round|Series C]] funding. Participants in this funding round include Emergence Capital, Horizons Ventures ([[Li Ka-shing]]), [[Qualcomm Ventures]], [[Jerry Yang]], and [[Patrick Soon-Shiong]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2015/02/04/fast-growing-zoom-raises-30-million-for-online-video-conferencing/ |title=Fast-Growing Zoom Raises $30 Million for Online Video Conferencing |publisher=Wall Street Journal |date=4 February 2015 |author=Gage, Deborah}}</ref> In November 2015, former president of [[RingCentral]] David Berman was named president of Zoom Video Communications, and the founder and [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of [[Veeva Systems]], [[Peter Gassner]], joined Zoom's [[board of directors]].<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.marketwired.com/press-release/zoom-names-new-president-david-berman-and-board-member-peter-gassner-2069595.htm |title=Zoom Names New President David Berman and Board Member Peter Gassner |publisher=MarketWired |date=3 November 2015 |accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Zoom had officially entered the [[Unicorn (finance)|unicorn]] club (US$1 [[billion]] valuation) and attracted US$100 million in Series D funding from [[Sequoia Capital]] at a billion dollar valuation. \n\nIn September 2017, Zoom hosted Zoomtopia 2017, Zoom's first annual user conference. Zoom announced a series of new products and partnerships, including Zoom's Partnership with Meta to integrate Zoom with [[Augmented Reality]], integration with Slack and Workplace by Facebook, and first steps towards an artificial intelligence speech-to-text converter.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/09/26/zoom-brings-a-dash-of-augmented-reality-and-artificial-intelligence-to-meetings-in-latest-release/ |title=Zoom brings a dash of augmented reality and artificial intelligence to meetings in latest&nbsp;release |last=Miller |first=Ron |work=TechCrunch |access-date=2017-11-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Zoom filed to go public on the [[NASDAQ]];<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/03/22/zoom-a-profitable-unicorn-files-to-go-public/ |title=Zoom, a profitable unicorn, files to go public |last=Clark |first=Kate |date=2019-03-22 |website=TechCrunch |language=en-US |archive-url= |archive-date= |access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref> on April 18, 2019, the company went public, with shares up more than 72%, with an [[Initial public offering]] of US$36 a share.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/18/tech/zoom-ipo-video-conference/index.html |title=Zoom nearly reaches $16 billion in value after first day of trading |last=Business |first=Ahiza Garcia, Sara O'Brien and Jordan Valinsky |date=2019-04-18 |website=CNN |archive-url= |archive-date= |access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref> The company was valued at just under US$16 billion by the end of its IPO.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Use during the COVID-19 pandemic ===\n{{seealso|Teleconferencing in the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\nIn 2020, usage of Zoom rose 67% from the start of the year to mid-March as schools and companies adopted the platform for [[Telecommuting|remote work]] in response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2020/03/14/zoom-is-helping-schools-closing-due-coronavirus-fo.aspx |title=Zoom Is Helping Schools Closing Due to Coronavirus -- for Free |last=Vena |first=Danny |date=2020-03-14 |website=The Motley Fool |language=en |access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> Since the pandemic intensified, thousands of educational institutions switched to online classes using Zoom.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Mervosh |first=Sarah |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/us/coronavirus-closings.html |title=Colleges and Universities Cancel Classes and Move Online Amid Coronavirus Fears |date=2020-03-10 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-03-26 |last2=Swales |first2=Vanessa |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2020/03/20/schooling-rapidly-moves-online-across-country-concerns-rise-about-student-data-privacy/ |title=As schooling rapidly moves online across the country, concerns rise about student data privacy |last=Strauss |first=Valerie |date=March 20, 2020 |website=The Washington post |url-status=live |archive-url= |archive-date= |access-date=}}</ref> The company offered its services to [[K\u201312]] schools free of charge in many countries.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alexkonrad/2020/03/13/zoom-video-coronavirus-eric-yuan-schools/ |title=Exclusive: Zoom CEO Eric Yuan Is Giving K-12 Schools His Videoconferencing Tools For Free |last=Konrad |first=Alex |website=Forbes |language=en |access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> In one day, the Zoom app was downloaded 343,000 times with about 18% of those downloads originating in the United States.<ref name=\":5\" /> Zoom gained over 2.22 million users in the first months of 2020\u2014more users than it amassed in the entirety of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/26/zoom-has-added-more-users-so-far-this-year-than-in-2019-bernstein.html |title=Zoom has added more videoconferencing users this year than in all of 2019 thanks to coronavirus, Bernstein says |last=Novet |first=Jordan |date=2020-02-26 |website=CNBC |language=en |access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Consequently, by March 2020, Zoom shares increased to US$160.98 per share, a 263% increase from initial share prices when it first went public.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/zoom-stock-price-surged-coronavirus-pandemic-video-work-from-home-2020-3-1029023594 |title=Zoom Video has seen its stock spike more than 100% since January as coronavirus pushes millions to work from home (ZM) |last=Reinicke |first=Carmen |date=23 March 2020 |website=markets.businessinsider.com |url-status=live |archive-url= |archive-date= |access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>  The company reported daily average users rose from about 10 million in December 2019 to about 200 million in March 2020.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2020/04/03/826129520/a-must-for-millions-zoom-has-a-dark-side-and-an-fbi-warning A Must For Millions, Zoom Has A Dark Side \u2014 And An FBI Warning]</ref>\n\nZoom also became a popular social platform over the course of the pandemic.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news |last=Lorenz |first=Taylor |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/style/zoom-parties-coronavirus-memes.html |title=We Live in Zoom Now |date=2020-03-17 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-03-26 |last2=Griffith |first2=Erin |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |last3=Isaac |first3=Mike}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/23/ok-zoomer-zoom-worlds-new-favourite-social-network-12443418/ |title=Ok Zoomer: Why Zoom is the world's new favourite social network |last=Parsons |first=Jeff |date=2020-03-23 |website=Metro |language=en |url-status=live |archive-url= |archive-date= |access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> [[Generation Z|Gen Z]] and [[Millennials]]{{dubious|date=April 2020}}<!-- some people outside these generations have no doubt also done so; arguably, this claim is ageist --> have connected with each other through events such as \"Zoom Blind Dates\", and \"Zoom Recess\".<ref name=\":4\" /> Zoom as a company has developed into an [[Internet meme]] and students at a number of colleges and universities have spread memes about its use as \"Zoom University\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Wagner |first=James |url=https://www.nytimes.com/live/2020/coronavirus-update-03-13 |title=How Coronavirus Is Changing Our Daily Lives: Latest Updates |date=2020-03-14 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-03-14 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Lorenz |first= Taylor |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/style/zoom-parties-coronavirus-memes.html |title=We Live in Zoom Now |date=March 17, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live |last2=Griffith |first2=Erin |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |last3=Isaac |first3=Mike}}</ref> Zoom has also gained popularity amongst older users and families separated by ongoing [[social distancing]] guidelines and mandates. These virtual social gatherings are often referred to as \"Zoom Parties\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/how-to-throw-zoom-party-custom-background-friends-family-2020-3 |title=How to throw a perfect Zoom party with your friends and family |last=Tenbarge |first=Kat |website=Business Insider |access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> \n\nWith the rise of videoconferencing, incidents of \"[[Zoombombing|{{Anchor|Zoombombing}}Zoombombing]]\", the practice of participants unexpectedly appearing in conferences and sending [[pornography]] or other offensive material to other attendees, have occurred,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2020/03/25/zoombombing-disrupts-online-classes-university-southern-california/ |title='Zoombombing' disrupts online classes at University of Southern California |website=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-03-25/zoombombing-usc-classes-interrupted-racist-remarks |title=USC, school districts getting 'Zoom-bombed' with racist taunts, porn as they transition to online meetings |date=March 25, 2020 |website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2020/03/17/zoombombing/ |title=Beware of 'ZoomBombing:' screensharing filth to video calls |date=March 18, 2020 |website=TechCrunch}}</ref> causing some organizations to abandon the use of Zoom.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor Lorenz |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/20/style/zoombombing-zoom-trolling.html |title='Zoombombing': When Video Conferences Go Wrong |work=The New York Times |accessdate=27 March 2020 |language=en |quote=On Tuesday, Chipotle was forced to end a public Zoom chat that the brand had co-hosted with the musician Lauv after one participant began broadcasting pornography to hundreds of attendees [...] \u201cWe did encounter an unwanted \u2018Zoombomb\u2019 during one of our sessions so we moved our latest performances to a different platform.\u201d}}</ref> To combat this, Zoom introduced a new feature which requires users to input a password as they join a meeting.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Akolawala |first1=Tasneem |title=Zoom Meeting App: New Security Features Introduced to Prevent Zoombombing, Thousands Saved Videos Reportedly Leak Online |url=https://gadgets.ndtv.com/apps/news/zoom-meeting-app-password-waiting-room-security-features-zoombombing-videos-leak-online-2206139 |website=Gadgets 360 |publisher=NDTV |accessdate=8 April 2020 |date=4 April 2020}}</ref> Additionally, they published a guide to reduce the chances of such incidents.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://blog.zoom.us/wordpress/2020/03/20/keep-the-party-crashers-from-crashing-your-zoom-event/ |title=How to Keep the Party Crashers from Crashing Your Zoom Event |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nZoom's data security and privacy practices have also come under increased scrutiny.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-52115434|title=Zoom under increased scrutiny as popularity soars|date=2020-04-01|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-GB}}</ref> Consequently, Zoom's CEO released a statement apologizing for the security issues.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/02/tech/zoom-ceo-apology-privacy/index.html|title=Zoom CEO apologizes for having 'fallen short' on privacy and security|last=Iyengar|first=Rishi|date=2 April 2020|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Some of the issues were a result of Zoom having been designed for \"large institutions with full IT support.\"<ref name=\":7\"/> To combat these issues, Zoom has said it will focus on data privacy and issue a transparency report.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Alex |last1=Hern |accessdate=2020-04-05|title=Zoom says engineers will focus on security and safety issues|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/apr/02/zoom-says-engineers-will-focus-on-security-and-safety-issues|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2 April 2020|issn=0261-3077|via=theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2020-04-05|title=SMBlog -- 2 April 2020|url=https://www.cs.columbia.edu/~smb/blog/2020-04/2020-04-02.html|author=[[Steven M. Bellovin]]}}</ref>\n\n== Products ==\nZoom provides video conferencing for up to 100 participants, with a 40-minute time limit. Beyond this, paid subscriptions are available to allow more participants, increase the time limit, and obtain more advanced features. Zoom claims that its software is compliant with [[FedRAMP]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://convergentav.net/2018/07/10/zoom-achieves-fedramp-in-process-milestone/|title=Zoom Achieves FedRAMP \"In Process\" Milestone|date=2018-07-10|website=Convergent|language=en|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref> [[Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act|HIPAA]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hipaajournal.com/zoom-hipaa-compliant/|title=Is Zoom a HIPAA Compliant Video and Web Conferencing Platform?|date=2018-02-19|website=HIPAA Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref> [[Personal Information Protection and Electronic Documents Act|PIPEDA]] and [[Personal Health Information Protection Act|PHIPA]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bitpipe.com/detail/RES/1548948281_430.html|title=Build patient engagement with compliant video conferencing|website=bitpipe.com|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref> and the [[General Data Protection Regulation|GDPR]], however these claims cannot be verified by security researchers around the world as the applications are [[Proprietary software|closed source]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/360000126326-Official-Statement-EU-GDPR-Compliance|title=Official Statement: EU GDPR Compliance|website=Zoom Help Center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> Zoom has received various industry recognitions for its products.<ref>{{cite web |title=Awards Archives |url=https://blog.zoom.us/wordpress/category/awards/ |website=Zoom blog |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nInitially, Zoom could host conferences with up to 15 video participants,<ref name=\"15participants\">{{cite web | url=https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10000872396390444443504577603383238616426?mg=reno64-wsj&url=http%3A%2F%2Fonline.wsj.com%2Farticle%2FSB10000872396390444443504577603383238616426.html | title=A Chance To Call 15 Friends To Video Chat In High Def | publisher=Wall Street Journal | date=21 August 2012 | author=[[Walt Mossberg|Mossberg, Walter S.]]}}</ref> increased to 25 in January 2013, to 100 with version 2.5 in October 2015,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.eweek.com/networking/zoom-doubles-capacity-of-video-conferencing-service-to-50.html | title=Zoom Doubles Capacity of Video Conferencing Service to 50 | publisher=eWeek | date=2 October 2015 | accessdate=19 November 2015 | author=Burt, Jeffrey}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://zoom.us/pricing|title=Video Conferencing, Web Conferencing, Webinars, Screen Sharing|website=Zoom Video|language=en-US|access-date=2017-11-29}}</ref> and later to 1,000 for business customers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/skype-vs-zoom-which-video-chat-app-is-best-for-working-from-home/|title=Skype vs. Zoom: Which video chat app is best for working from home?|first=Shelby|last=Brown|date=10 March 2020|work=CNET|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>  Between 2015 and mid-2016, Zoom Video Communications announced native support for [[Skype for Business]] and integration with [[Slack (software)|Slack]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.zoom.us/wordpress/2015/08/13/zoom-slack-integration/|title=Announcement: Zoom Slack Integration|last=|first=|date=13 August 2015|website=Zoom Blog|publisher=|access-date=8 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msn.com/en-us/money/other/zoom-announces-native-skype-for-business-interoperability/ar-BBr50fP|title=Zoom Announces Native Skype for Business Interoperability|website=msn.com|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, Zoom announced integration of Zoom video conferencing with [[Salesforce]]'s [[customer relationship management]] platform, allowing salespeople to initiate such conferences with their [[sales lead]]s without leaving the application.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tmcnet.com/channels/ip-phones/articles/409907-zoom-announces-salesforce-integration.htm|title=Zoom Announces Salesforce Integration|author=Delony, David|date=15 September 2015|publisher=TMCnet|accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref> In April 2017, Zoom launched Telehealth, a scalable [[telehealth]] product allowing doctors to remotely visit their patients through video for consultation.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://conferencing.tmcnet.com/topics/conferencing/articles/431502-zoom-introduces-new-telehealth-solution.htm |title=Zoom Introduces New Telehealth Solution |last=Young |first=Alicia |date=24 April 2017 |work=TMCnet |access-date=7 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.globenewswire.com/news-release/2017/04/20/1311124/0/en/Zoom-Launches-Industry-s-First-Scalable-Cloud-Based-Video-Telehealth-Solution.html|title=Zoom Launches Industry's First Scalable Cloud-Based Video Telehealth Solution|first=Zoom Video Communications|last=Inc|date=April 20, 2017|website=GlobeNewswire News Room}}</ref> In May 2017, Zoom announced a partnership with [[Polycom]] that integrated Zoom's video meetings into Polycom's conferencing systems, enabling features such as multiple screen and device meetings, HD and wireless screen sharing, and calendar integration with [[Microsoft Outlook]], [[Google Calendar]], and [[iCal]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/polycom-zoom-forge-video-conferencing-collaboration-pact/|title=Polycom, Zoom forge video conferencing, collaboration pact {{!}} ZDNet|last=Dignan|first=Larry|date=2017-05-25|work=ZDNet|access-date=2017-11-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n\n===Privacy===\nZoom has been criticized for its [[Digital hoarding|data hoarding]] practices,<ref>{{cite web |last1=St. John |first1=Allen |title=Zoom Calls Aren't as Private as You May Think. Here's What You Should Know. |url=https://www.consumerreports.org/video-conferencing-services/zoom-teleconferencing-privacy-concerns/ |website=Consumer Reports |accessdate=26 March 2020 |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> which include its collection and storage of \"the content contained in cloud recordings, and instant messages, files, whiteboards\" as well as its enabling employers to monitor workers remotely;<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kate O'Flaherty |title=Zoom's A Lifeline During COVID-19: This Is Why It's Also A Privacy Risk |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kateoflahertyuk/2020/03/25/zooms-a-lifeline-during-covid-19-this-is-why-its-also-a-privacy-risk/#508f8eb428ba |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=Forbes |date=25 March 2020 |language=en |quote=collects and stores personal data and shares it with third parties such as advertisers. But Zoom\u2019s policy also covers what it labels \u201ccustomer content,\u201d or \"the content contained in cloud recordings, and instant messages, files, whiteboards ... shared while using the service.\"  This includes videos, transcripts that can be generated automatically, documents shared on screen, and the names of everyone on a call.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Morse |first1=Jack |title=Zoom is a work-from-home privacy disaster waiting to happen |url=https://mashable.com/article/zoom-conference-call-work-from-home-privacy-concerns/ |website=Mashable |accessdate=26 March 2020 |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> the [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]] warned that administrators can join any call at any time \"without in-the-moment consent or warning for the attendees of the call.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2020/03/what-you-should-know-about-online-tools-during-covid-19-crisis|title=What You Should Know About Online Tools During the COVID-19 Crisis|first=Lindsay|last=Oliver|date=March 19, 2020|website=Electronic Frontier Foundation}}</ref>   During signup for a Zoom free account, Zoom requires users to permit it to identify users with their personal information on Google and also offers to permanently delete their Google contacts.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nWidespread use of Zoom for online education during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|novel coronavirus pandemic]] increased concerns regarding students' data privacy and, in particular, their [[Personal data|personally identifiable information]].<ref name=\":2\" /> According to the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]], students\u2019 IP addresses, browsing history, academic progress, and biometric data may be at risk during the use of similar online learning services.<ref name=\":2\" /> Privacy experts are also concerned that the use of Zoom by schools and universities may raise issues regarding unauthorized surveillance of students and possible violations of students\u2019 rights under the [[Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act]] (FERPA).<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2020/03/25/pivot-online-raises-concerns-ferpa-surveillance|title=Pivot to online raises concerns for FERPA, surveillance|last=St. Amour|first=Madeline|date=|website=insidehighered.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> The company claims that the video services are FERPA-compliant, and also claims that it collects and stores user data only to \"provide technical and operational support\".<ref name=\":3\" />  \n\nThe company's [[iOS]] app was found to be sending device analytics data to Facebook on startup, regardless of whether a Facebook account was being used with the service, and without mentioning it to the user.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/k7e599/zoom-ios-app-sends-data-to-facebook-even-if-you-dont-have-a-facebook-account|title=Zoom iOS App Sends Data to Facebook Even if You Don't Have a Facebook Account|last=Cox|first=Joseph|date=2020-03-26|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> On March 27, Zoom stated that it had been \"recently made aware that the Facebook [[Software development kit|SDK]] was collecting unnecessary device data\", and that it had patched the app to remove the SDK (which was primarily used for [[social login]] support) in order to address these concerns. The company stated that the SDK was only collecting information on the user's device specifications (such as model names and operating system versions), and was not collecting personal information.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/z3b745/zoom-removes-code-that-sends-data-to-facebook|title=Zoom Removes Code That Sends Data to Facebook|last=Cox|first=Joseph|date=2020-03-27|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> In April 2020, The [[New York Times]] reported that a data-mining feature on Zoom automatically sent user names and email addresses to [[LinkedIn]] via a tool meant to match user profiles, allowing some participants to surreptitiously access LinkedIn profile data about other users.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Aaron Krolik|last2=Natasha Singer|title=A Feature on Zoom Secretly Displayed Data From People's LinkedIn Profiles|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/02/technology/zoom-linkedin-data.html|accessdate=3 April 2020|work=[[The New York Times]]|language=en|quote=as high school students in Colorado signed in to a mandatory video meeting for a class, Zoom readied the full names and email addresses of at least six students \u2014 and their teacher \u2014 for possible use by its LinkedIn profile-matching tool, according to a Times analysis of the data traffic that Zoom sent to a student\u2019s account.}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Zoom was sued in U.S. Federal Court for illegally disclosing personal data to third parties including Facebook. According to the suit, Zoom's privacy policy does not explain to users that its app contains code that discloses information to Facebook and potentially other third parties. The company's \"wholly inadequate program design and security measures have resulted, and will continue to result, in unauthorized disclosure of its users\u2019 personal information,\" according to the complaint.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rosenblatt |first1=Joel |title=Zoom Sued for Allegedly Illegally Disclosing Personal Data |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-31/zoom-sued-for-allegedly-illegally-disclosing-personal-data |website=Bloomberg}}</ref> The same month, the [[New York State Attorney General]], [[Letitia James]] launched an inquiry into Zoom's privacy and security practices.<ref name=\"nytimes-hakim-singer\"/><ref name=\"ft-murphy\"/>\n\n=== Security ===\n{{further|Zoombombing}}\n\nZoom claims to use [[TLS 1.2]] with [[Advanced Encryption Standard]] 256-bit (AES-256) for the Zoom client. In details, Zoom uses TLS 1.2 with AES-256 to protect [[Signaling (telecommunications)|signaling]], and uses AES-128 to protect [[Streaming media|audio and video streams]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/201362723-Encryption-for-Meetings |title=Encryption for Meetings &ndash; Zoom Help Center |date= |website=Zoom |language=en-US |access-date=2020-04-07 }}</ref>Zoom claims to use \"[[end-to-end encryption]]\" in its marketing materials,<ref>{{Cite web|url=hhttps://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/207599823-End-To-End-Encryption-for-Chat |title=End-To-End Encryption for Chat &ndash; Zoom Help Center |date= |website=Zoom |language=en-US |access-date=2020-04-07 }}</ref> but later clarified it meant \"from Zoom end point to Zoom end point\" (meaning effectively between Zoom servers and Zoom clients), which is misleading and has been described as \"dishonest\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2020/03/31/zoom-meeting-encryption/|title=Zoom Meetings Aren't End-to-End Encrypted, Despite Misleading Marketing|last=Lee|first=Micah|last2=Grauer|first2=Yael|date=2020-03-31|website=The Intercept|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31|quote=Currently, it is not possible to enable E2E encryption for Zoom video meetings. (...) When we use the phrase \u2018End to End\u2019 in our other literature, it is in reference to the connection being encrypted from Zoom end point to Zoom end point.}}</ref> [[CitizenLab|Citizenlab]] researchers also discovered that in reality a single, server-generated AES-128 key is being shared between all participants in [[Block cipher mode of operation|ECB mode]], which is deprecated due to its pattern-preserving characteristics of the ciphertext. During test calls between participants in Canada and USA the key was provisioned from servers located in mainland China where they are subject to the [[China Internet Security Law]].<ref name=\"citizenlab\">{{Cite web|url=https://citizenlab.ca/2020/04/move-fast-roll-your-own-crypto-a-quick-look-at-the-confidentiality-of-zoom-meetings/|title=Move Fast & Roll Your Own Crypto: A Quick Look at the Confidentiality of Zoom Meetings|date=2020-04-03|website=The Citizen Lab|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> \n\nIn November 2018, a security vulnerability ({{CVE|2018-15715}}) was discovered<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2018-15715 |title=CVE-2018-15715 |website=National Vulnerability Database |access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref> that allowed a remote unauthenticated attacker to spoof UDP messages from a meeting attendee or Zoom server in order to invoke functionality in the target client. This would allow the attacker to remove attendees from meetings, spoof messages from users, or hijack shared screens. Another vulnerability allowing the client unprompted access to camera and microphone was made public on April 1st, 2020, and was fixed by the evening ([https://cve.mitre.org/cgi-bin/cvename.cgi?name=CVE-2020-11470 CVE-2020-11470]).<ref>{{cite journal |title=The Zoom Privacy Backlash Is Only Getting Started |journal=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |date=Apr 1, 2020 |url=https://www.wired.com/story/zoom-backlash-zero-days/}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, security researcher Jonathan Leitschuh disclosed<ref>{{cite web |url=https://medium.com/@jonathan.leitschuh/zoom-zero-day-4-million-webcams-maybe-an-rce-just-get-them-to-visit-your-website-ac75c83f4ef5 |title=Zoom Zero Day: 4+ Million Webcams & maybe an RCE? Just get them to visit your website! |last=Leitschuh |first=Jonathan |date=2019-07-09 |website=Medium |language=en |access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref> a [[zero-day (computing)|zero-day]] vulnerability allowing any website to forcibly join a [[macOS]] user to a Zoom call, with their video camera activated, without the user's permission. In addition, attempts to uninstall the Zoom client on macOS would prompt the software to re-install automatically in the background, using a hidden web server that was set up on the machine during the first installation and remained active even after attempting to remove the client. After receiving public criticism, Zoom updated their software to remove the vulnerability and the hidden webserver, allowing complete uninstallation.<ref name=\"Anderson 2019\">{{cite web | last=Anderson | first=Tim | title=Anyone for unintended Chat Roulette? Zoom installs hidden Mac web server to allow auto-join video conferencing | website=The Register | date=2019-07-09 | url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2019/07/09/zooms_hidden_mac_web_server_allows_autojoin_conferencing_exploit/ | access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nThe increased use of Zoom during the coronavirus pandemic caused increased scrutiny of Zoom's security, including cases where Windows users' [[Credential#Information technology|credentials]] could be exposed.<ref>{{cite news |first=Dan |last=Goodin |title=Attackers can use Zoom to steal users' Windows credentials with no warning |url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2020/04/unpatched-zoom-bug-lets-attackers-steal-windows-credentials-with-no-warning/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[Ars Technica]] |date=1 April 2020 |language=en |quote=The vulnerability was first described last week by a researcher who uses the Twitter handle @_g0dmode. He wrote: \u201c#Zoom chat allows you to post links such as \\\\x.x.x.x\\xyz to attempt to capture Net-NTLM hashes if clicked by other users.}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |author=Mitch |user=_g0dmode |number=1242131019026874369 |date=2020-03-23 |title=#Zoom chat allows you to post links such as \\\\x.x.x.x\\xyz to attempt to capture Net-NTLM hashes if clicked by other users.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/zoom-lets-attackers-steal-windows-credentials-run-programs-via-unc-links/|title=Zoom Lets Attackers Steal Windows Credentials, Run Programs via UNC Links|website=BleepingComputer|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Zoom-related [[phishing]] scams also emerged, such as an increase of fake Zoom websites and links created to steal personal information.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.computerweekly.com/news/252480806/Coronavirus-Warning-over-surge-in-Zoom-security-incidents|title=Coronavirus: Warning over surge in Zoom security incidents|last=Scroxton|first=Alex|date=30 March 2020|website=ComputerWeekly.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> \"[[Zoombombing]]\", when an unwanted participant joins a meeting to cause disruption, also increased, prompting a warning from the [[FBI]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/contact-us/field-offices/boston/news/press-releases/fbi-warns-of-teleconferencing-and-online-classroom-hijacking-during-covid-19-pandemic|title=FBI Warns of Teleconferencing and Online Classroom Hijacking During COVID-19 Pandemic|date=30 March 2020|website=fbi.gov}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first1=Alex |last1=Hern |accessdate=2020-04-05|title=Trolls exploit Zoom privacy settings as app gains popularity|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/mar/27/trolls-zoom-privacy-settings-covid-19-lockdown|newspaper=The Guardian|date=27 March 2020|issn=0261-3077|via=theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, Zoom admitted that some Zoom calls were being routed through servers in mainland China. Zoom Video Communications offered an apology but only a partial explanation.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Zack |last1=Whittaker|accessdate=2020-04-05|title=Zoom admits some calls were routed through China by mistake|url=https://techcrunch.com/2020/04/03/zoom-calls-routed-china|newspaper=TechCrunch|date=4 April 2020}}</ref> In April, the New York Attorney General has issued a number of official and explicit questions about Zoom.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Jerry |last1=McNerney|accessdate=2020-04-05|title=Rep. McNerney and Colleagues Push Zoom for Answers About the Company's Privacy Practices|url=https://mcnerney.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/rep-mcnerney-and-colleagues-push-zoom-for-answers-about-the-company-s|date=3 April 2020}}</ref> Further, in April 2020, security researchers with [[Citizen_Lab|The Citizen Lab]] issued a report that concluded that Zoom features significant security and encryption weaknesses. <ref>{{cite news|first1=Bill Marczak|last1=John Scott-Railton|accessdate=2020-04-05|title= Move Fast & Roll Your Own Crypto: A Quick Look at the Confidentiality of Zoom Meetings|url=https://citizenlab.ca/2020/04/move-fast-roll-your-own-crypto-a-quick-look-at-the-confidentiality-of-zoom-meetings|newspaper=The Citizen Lab|date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn light of numerous privacy and security concerns,<ref>{{cite news|first1=Kari|last1=Paul|accessdate=2020-04-05|title='Zoom is malware': why experts worry about the video conferencing platform|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/apr/02/zoom-technology-security-coronavirus-video-conferencing|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2 April 2020|issn=0261-3077|via=theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2020-04-05|title=Is Zoom safe and can it be hacked?|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/features/zoom-safe-hack-how-secure-encryption-a9440461.html|date=2 April 2020|website=The Independent}}</ref> in March 2020 the [[New York State Attorney General]], [[Letitia James]], launched an inquiry into Zoom's privacy and security practices.<ref name=\"nytimes-hakim-singer\">{{cite news|first1=Danny|last1=Hakim|first2=Natasha|last2=Singer|accessdate=2020-04-04|title=New York Attorney General Looks Into Zoom's Privacy Practices|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/30/technology/new-york-attorney-general-zoom-privacy.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=30 March 2020|issn=0362-4331|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref name=\"ft-murphy\">{{cite web|accessdate=2020-04-05|title=Privacy concerns grow over Zoom videoconferencing platform|url=https://www.ft.com/content/bdedc70b-e559-489e-bfa0-445b9c882f7b|website=ft.com}}</ref> Following these inquiries, Zoom was banned from New York City schools by the [[New York City Department of Education]] due to security and privacy issues with the platform.<ref name=\"FastCo\">{{cite news|first1=Ainsley |last1=Harris|accessdate=2020-04-05|title=Zoom banned from New York City schools due to privacy and security flaws|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/90486586/zoom-banned-from-new-york-city-schools-due-to-privacy-and-security-flaws|newspaper=Fast Company|date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Bans===\nDue to the various privacy and security concerns, numerous organizations and government entities have banned the use of Zoom:\n\n*[[Australian Defence Force]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tim Biggs|title=Zoom says it's safe for Australian companies to use as security concerns escalate|url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/zoom-says-it-s-safe-for-australian-companies-to-use-as-security-concerns-escalate-20200406-p54hj0.html|accessdate=7 April 2020|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=7 April 2020|language=en|quote=the Australian Defence Force banning its members from using the service}}</ref>\n\n*[[Berkeley, California]] (public school use)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eastbaytimes.com/2020/04/08/zoom-bombers-disrupt-berkeley-schools/|title=Zoom bomber exposed himself to Berkeley High students, school official says|date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n*[[Canada]] (Federal government use that requires secure communications)<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2020-04-08|title=Taiwan joins Canada in banning Zoom for government video conferencing|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/taiwan-zoom-video-conference-1.5524384|website=CBC News|date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n*[[Clark County, Nevada]] (public school use)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/local/education/clark-county-schools-ban-zoom-app-over-security-concerns-1997093/|title=Clark County schools ban Zoom app over security concerns|date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> \n\n*[[German Ministry of Foreign Affairs]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/german-government-restricts-use-of-zoom-over-security-concerns-reports/a-53069274|title=German government restricts use of Zoom over security concerns - reports &#124; DW &#124; 08.04.2020|first=Deutsche|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|website=DW.COM}}</ref>\n\n*[[Google]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/google-bans-zoom-from-employee-computers-due-to-security-concerns-2020-4|title=Google has banned the Zoom app from all employee computers over 'security vulnerabilities'|first=Hugh|last=Langley|website=Business Insider}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/technology/google-bans-its-employees-from-using-zoom-over-security-concerns/ar-BB12kZKT|title=Google bans its employees from using Zoom over security concerns|website=msn.com}}</ref>\n\n*[[NASA]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Elon Musk's SpaceX bans Zoom over privacy concerns, memo shows |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/01/elon-musks-spacex-bans-zoom-over-privacy-concerns-memo-shows.html |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=CNBC |date=1 April 2020 |language=en |quote=NASA, one of SpaceX\u2019s biggest customers, also prohibits its employees from using Zoom, said Stephanie Schierholz, a spokeswoman for the U.S. space agency.}}</ref>\n\n*[[New York City]] (public school use)<ref>{{cite news|last=Harris|first1=Ainsley|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/90486586/zoom-banned-from-new-york-city-schools-due-to-privacy-and-security-flaws|title=Zoom banned from New York City schools due to privacy and security flaws|date=5 April 2020|newspaper=Fast Company|accessdate=2020-04-05|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*[[Singapore Ministry of Education]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-zoom-video-comm-privacy-singapore-idUSKCN21S0AH|title=Singapore stops teachers using Zoom app after very serious incidents|date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/moe-suspends-zoom-home-based-learning-obscene-images-12626534|title=MOE suspends use of Zoom in home-based learning following breaches involving obscene images|date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n*[[Smart Communications]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://micky.com.au/major-philippine-telco-bans-internal-use-of-zoom-cites-security-risks/|title=Major Philippine telco bans internal use of Zoom, cites security risks|date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n*[[SpaceX]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/04/02/business/02reuters-spacex-zoom-video-commn.html|title=Elon Musk's SpaceX Bans Zoom Over Privacy Concerns - Memo|date=2 April 2020|website=nytimes.com|language=en}}</ref>\n\n*[[Taiwan]] (government use)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Debby Wu|last2=Samson Ellis|title=Taiwan Bans Government Use of Zoom Over Cybersecurity Concerns|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-07/taiwan-bans-government-use-of-zoom-over-cybersecurity-concerns|accessdate=7 April 2020|work=[[Bloomberg L.P.]