ry|8 times]]) \u2013 with [[Stan Lane]] (5) and Jimmy Del Ray (3)<ref name=SMWTag>{{cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2000|edition=4th |chapter= (Tennessee) Knoxville: Smokey Mountain Wrestling Tag Team Title|isbn=0-9698161-5-4}}</ref><ref>[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/tn/knoxville/smw/smw-t.html SMW Tag Team Title history] At wrestling-titles.com</ref>\n*'''[[United States Wrestling Association]]'''\n**[[Memphis Wrestling Southern Heavyweight Championship|USWA Southern Heavyweight Championship]] ([[Memphis Wrestling Southern Heavyweight Championship#Title history|6 times]])<ref name=USWASouth>[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/tn/uswa/uswa-s-h.html USWA Southern Heavyweight Title history] At wrestling-titles.com</ref>\n**[[NWA Texas Heavyweight Championship|USWA Texas Heavyweight Championship]] ([[NWA Texas Heavyweight Championship#Title history|2 times]])<ref name=TexasBook>{{cite book| last1=Will | first1=Gary | first2=Royal | last2= Duncan | title=Wrestling Title Histories: professional wrestling champions around the world from the 19th century to the present | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2000 | location=Pennsylvania | chapter=Texas: NWA Texas Heavyweight Title [Von Erich] | isbn=0-9698161-5-4 | pages=268\u2013269}}</ref><ref name=USWATexas>{{cite web | url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/tx/tx-h.html | title= NWA Texas Heavyweight Title | accessdate=March 30, 2017 | work=Wrestling-Titles}}</ref>\n**[[USWA World Tag Team Championship]] ([[USWA World Tag Team Championship#Title history|1 time]]) \u2013 with Jimmy Del Ray<ref>{{cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2000|edition=4th |chapter= (Tennessee) Memphis: United States Wrestling Association Tag Team Title|isbn=0-9698161-5-4 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/tn/uswa/uswa-t.html USWA World Tag Team Title history] At wrestling-titles.com</ref>\n*'''United Wrestling Association'''\n**UWA Southern Heavyweight Championship (1 time)\n**UWA Texas Heavyweight Championship (1 time)\n*'''[[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]]'''\n**[[World Tag Team Championship|WWF Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of World Tag Team Champions|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Chris Candido|Skip]]<ref name=WWFTag>[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/wwe/wwf-t.html WWWF/WWF/WWE World Tag Team Title history] At wrestling-titles.com</ref><ref name=WWF9099Book/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0698081|name=Tom Prichard}}\n*[http://www.worldwrestlinginsanity.com/artman/publish/drtom.shtml Prichard's opinion column at WorldWrestlingInsanity.com]\n*[http://bodyslamming.com/wwe/prichard.html Tom Prichard at Bodyslamming.com]\n*[http://www.cagematch.de/cgi-bin/database/english/profile.cgi?action=overview&worker=00000380 Tom Prichard at Cagematch.de]\n*[http://www.gerweck.net/tomprichard.htm Tom Prichard at Gerweck.net]\n*[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/ca/la/hw/ams-t.html Wrestling-Titles.com]\n{{SMW Tag Team Championship}}\n{{World Tag Team Championship (WWE)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Prichard, Tom}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Houston]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from Texas]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling trainers]]\n[[Category:The Stud Stable members]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the cricketer|Tom Pritchard}}\n{{redirect|Doctor Tom|the historian|Thomas Richards (historian)}}\n{{short description|American retired professional wrestler and trainer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = Tom Prichard\n|image       = Tom_Prichard_(wrestler).jpg\n|alt         =\n|caption     = Prichard in January 2020\n|birth_name  = Thomas Prichard\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1959|8|18}}<ref name=oww/>\n|birth_place = [[Pasadena, Texas]]<ref name=oww/>\n|death_date  =\n|family      = [[Bruce Prichard]] (brother)\n|spouse      = Sandi Prichard\n|death_place =\n|resides     =\n|names       = Dr. Tom Prichard<ref name=oww/><br />Dr. X<ref name=oww/><br />'''Tom Prichard'''<ref name=Alumni/><br />Zip<ref name=Alumni>{{cite web|title=Tom Prichard|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/wwealumni/tom-prichard|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=March 7, 2012}}</ref>\n|height      = {{height|ft=5|in=10}}<ref name=Alumni/>\n|weight      = {{convert|230|lb|abbr=on}}<ref name=Alumni/>\n|billed      = [[Houston, Texas]]<ref name=Alumni/>\n|trainer     = [[The Iron Sheik]]\n|debut       = 1979\n|retired     =  2017\n}}\n'''Thomas Prichard''' (born August 18, 1959) is a retired American [[professional wrestling|professional wrestler]] and author. He is the father of Chris Prichard and brother of [[Bruce Prichard]].<ref name=oww>{{cite web |url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/t/tom-prichard.html |title=Tom Prichard profile |accessdate=2009-11-20 |publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Beginnings (1979 - 1986)===\nTom Prichard began his career in Los Angeles, around 1979, working for Gene and Mike LeBell's Los Angeles Olympic Auditorium wrestling promotion, where he held several championships in that organization, including the Americas tag team title with [[Chris Adams (wrestler)|Chris Adams]]. After LeBell closed the L.A. promotion down in 1982, Prichard competed in various NWA territories for the next four years before settling in the southeast, where he had his greatest success of his career.\n\n===Continental Championship Wrestling / Continental Wrestling Federation (1986 - 1989)===\n\nPrichard joined [[Continental Championship Wrestling]] in 1986, and by 1988, he feuded with \"The Dirty White Boy\" [[Tony Anthony (wrestler)|Tony Anthony]]. Their feud included a very controversial angle, which aired on April 23, 1988, where Anthony's valet came out with a black eye and begged Prichard to help her, only for Anthony to attack him from behind, cuff his hands behind his back, and hang him. On October 3, 1988 in [[Birmingham, Alabama]], he defeated Anthony in the finals of a tournament to win the vacant [[NWA Southeast Continental Heavyweight Championship|CWF Heavyweight Championship]].<ref name=CWFHeavy/> Prichard lost the title to [[Wendell Cooley]] on April 7, 1989 in Knoxville, Tennessee, but regained the belt on June 23 of that year.<ref name=CWFHeavy/> He lost the title to [[Dennis Condrey]] a month later on July 22 in [[Dothan, Alabama]], before once again regaining it after defeating Condrey on December 6 of that same year.<ref name=CWFHeavy/> Prichard held the title until the CWF closed later that month.<ref name=CWFHeavy/>\n\n===United States Wrestling Association (1990 - 1992)===\nIn 1990, Prichard then moved on to the [[United States Wrestling Association]], first working out of the Texas branch, where he formed a heel stable that included [[Eric Embry]] and [[Stone Cold Steve Austin|Steve Austin]], managed by [[Tojo Yamamoto]]. They feuded with the other top babyfaces, including [[Jeff Jarrett]], [[Bill Dundee]], [[Robert Fuller]], and others. While based out of Texas, Prichard won both the [[AWA Southern Heavyweight Championship|USWA Southern Heavyweight championship]] and the [[NWA Texas Heavyweight Championship|USWA Texas Heavyweight championship]] before the USWA closed the Texas end of their territory in November 1990.<ref name=USWASouth/><ref name=USWATexas/> Afterwards, Prichard competed in the Memphis end of the USWA before the opening of [[Smoky Mountain Wrestling]] in 1992.\n\n===Smoky Mountain Wrestling and World Wrestling Federation (1992 - 1995)===\n{{Main|The Heavenly Bodies|The Bodydonnas}}\n[[Stan Lane]] and Prichard formed a team as \"[[The Heavenly Bodies]]\" and joined [[Smoky Mountain Wrestling]] upon its formation in 1992, and on April 23, 1992, in [[Harrogate, Tennessee]], they defeated [[The Fantastics]] to become the first [[SMW Tag Team Championship|SMW Tag Team Champions]].<ref name=SMWTag/> They continued to feud with The Fantastics throughout mid-1992, and were finally defeated for the titles on August 8, 1992 in a [[barbed wire]] [[Professional wrestling match types#Cages|cage match]] in Johnson City, Tennessee. The Heavenly Bodies regained the titles two days later, holding them for three months before losing to the [[Rock 'N Roll Express]] on November 13, 1992 in a hospital elimination match in [[Harlan, Kentucky]].<ref name=SMWTag/> They traded the titles with the Rock 'N Roll Express three times in a variety of [[hardcore wrestling|hardcore]] matches over the following year before Lane left the promotion and retired from the ring.<ref name=SMWTag/><ref name=PWIYears100/>\n\nPrichard reformed the Heavenly Bodies with [[Jimmy Del Ray]], and the two competed in both SMW and the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]], wrestling the [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|WWF World tag team champions]] the [[Steiner Brothers]] at [[SummerSlam (1993)|SummerSlam 1993]].<ref name=Alumni/><ref name=\"ss93\">{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/summer.html#93|title=SummerSlam|work=Pro Wrestling History|accessdate=December 30, 2015}}</ref> On November 24, 1993 in Boston on the World Wrestling Federation's [[pay-per-view]] [[Survivor Series (1993)|Survivor Series 1993]], Prichard and Del Ray defeated the Rock 'N Roll Express.<ref name=WWF9099Book>{{cite book | first=Graham | last=Cawthon | title=the History of Professional Wrestling Vol 2: WWF 1990 - 1999  | publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform | year= 2013 | asin=B00RWUNSRS}}</ref> The Rock 'N Roll Express regained the titles on February 18, 1994 in Port Huron, Michigan, but lost the titles to the Heavenly Bodies on the following day in Taylor, Michigan.<ref name=SMWTag/> At [[WrestleMania X]] the Heavenly Bodies defeated the Bushwhackers in a dark match.<ref name=wwf1994>{{cite web|title=1994|work=The History of WWE|url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/94.htm|accessdate=December 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Rock 'N Roll Express defeated the Heavenly Bodies on April 1, 1994 in Pikeville, Kentucky in a \"[[Professional wrestling match types#Retirement match|Loser Leaves SMW match]]\", where they then competed in the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] for about a year, before being released in the summer of 1995.<ref name=WWF9099Book/> Prichard fought in a couple of single matches against Bret Hart and Shawn Michaels. They returned to SMW and regained the SMW Tag Team Championship, marking Prichard's eighth title reign, on August 4, 1995 in [[Knoxville, Tennessee]], defeating [[Tracy Smothers]] and [[Tony Anthony (wrestler)|Dirty White Boy]] at the Super Bowl of Wrestling.<ref name=SMWTag/> During the feud, The Thugs injured Prichard's leg, and he began wearing a loaded boot, which he use as a weapon to gain victories for him and Del Ray. They held the titles until the promotion folded on November 26, 1995.<ref name=SMWTag/> After SMW folded, the Heavenly Bodies briefly wrestled for [[Extreme Championship Wrestling]], until Prichard returned to the WWF.\n\n===Return to the WWF (1995 - 2004)===\nPrichard competed under his own name with his Heavenly Bodies attire at the [[Survivor Series (1995)|Survivor Series 1995]], wrestling on future tag team partner [[Chris Candido|Skip]]'s team \"[[The Bodydonnas]].\"  Prichard was the first man eliminated as the Bodydonnas defeated [[Barry Horowitz]]'s \"Underdogs\" team. A month later, Prichard was officially introduced as Zip, Skip's on-screen cousin and tag team partner,<ref name=Alumni/> interfering in a match allowing Skip to defeat [[Louie Spicolli|Rad Radford]], who had been trying to become a Bodydonna himself.<ref name=WWF9099Book/> Before this appearance he had cut off his trademark curly long brown locks into a blond crew cut, to more resemble his storyline cousin.<ref name=WWF9099Book/>\n\nOn the ''[[WrestleMania XII]]'' pre-show, on March 31, 1996, the team defeated [[The Godwinns]] in the finals of an eight team tournament to win the vacant [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|WWF Tag Team Championship]].<ref name=WWF9099Book/><ref name=WWFTag/> They held the titles until May 19, 1996, when they were defeated by the Godwinns in [[Madison Square Garden]] in New York City.<ref name=WWFTag/> After Skip left the WWF in fall of 1996, Prichard became a masked jobber named Dr.X. Dr. X fought mainly on house shows but made a few TV appearances on Superstars.<ref name=WWF9099Book/> Dr. X lost to [[Achim Albrecht|Brakkus]] at [[In Your House 12: It's Time]].<ref name=WWF9099Book/> By 1997, he became a trainer for the company, responsible for training such future stars as [[Dwayne Johnson|The Rock]], [[Kurt Angle]], and [[Mark Henry]], among others. On September 27, 1999, Prichard teamed up with [[Jeff Jarrett]] to face against [[Chyna]] and [[Debra Marshall|Debra]] on Raw Is War.<ref name=WWF9099Book/> Prichard hit Chyna with a guitar and Jarrett was knocked out cold as Chyna went for the victory.<ref name=WWF9099Book/> In addition, Prichard made a few appearances as a singles wrestler for ECW, and also co-hosted ''Byte This!'',<ref>{{IMDb title|5859428|WWE Byte This!}}</ref> the WWF's internet talk show. Prichard was released from WWE in 2004.\n\n===Independent circuit (2004 - 2007)===\nHe went on to wrestle in the United Wrestling Association and in various other [[independent circuit|independent]] [[professional wrestling promotion|promotions]] in the Southeastern United States. He also holds training seminars in conjunction with certain promotions. During this time Prichard also befriended online professional wrestling journalist James Guttman of World Wrestling Insanity and provided a weekly commentary on the world of [[pro wrestling]] entitled Tuesdays with Tom. On August 10, 2006, eight days prior to his 47th birthday, he became the oldest man to win the United Wrestling Association Heavyweight Championship, defeating Dillinger for the title.\n\n===Return to WWE (2007\u20132012)===\nIn January 2007, he was rehired by WWE and replaced [[Bill DeMott]] as the head trainer for [[Deep South Wrestling]] (DSW).\nWhen DSW closed, he was moved to WWE's new developmental territory [[Florida Championship Wrestling]]. On May 30, 2012, Prichard was released from the WWE, being replaced by Bill DeMott as the head trainer.\n\n===Independent Circuit (2017)===\nIn 2017, Dr. Tom Prichard had a match in Runcorn Wrestling Academy (RWA) in which he teamed in an 8 man tag team match with the owner of the RWA and former trainee of Dr. Tom Prichard in OVW, Andreas Rossi (Andy Baker), Chris Von Sharpe and Connor \u201cThe Bullet\u201d Stafford to take on the team of \u201cFantastic\u201d Matt Fox, Demoni, Johnathan Alexander and Mr. Williams. At the end of this match both Dr. Tom Prichard and Andreas Rossi both announced that this was their last match.\n\n==Wrestlers trained==\n*[[Kurt Angle]]\n*[[Sean Morley|Val Venis]]\n*[[Dwayne Johnson|The Rock]]\n*[[Shane McMahon]]\n*[[Giant Silva]]\n*[[The Bella Twins]]\n*[[Steve Bradley]]\n*[[Dolph Ziggler]]\n*[[Achim Albrecht|Brakkus]]\n*[[Cheeseburger (wrestler)|Cheeseburger]]\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''All-Star Wrestling'''\n**ASW Southern Heavyweight Championship (1 time)\n*'''American Wrestling Council'''\n**AWC Heavyweight Championship (1 time)\n*'''Five Star Wrestling'''\n**FSW Tag Team Championship (1 time) \u2013 with Smack Johnson\n*'''Global Championship Wrestling'''\n**Texas Heavyweight Championship (1 time)\n*'''[[National Wrestling Alliance|NWA Hollywood Wrestling]]'''\n**[[NWA Americas Tag Team Championship]] ([[NWA Americas Tag Team Championship#Title history|5 times]]) \u2013 with Apollo Jalisco (2), [[Alberto Madril]] (2), and [[Chris Adams (wrestler)|Chris Adams]] (1)<ref>[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/ca/la/hw/ams-t.html NWA Americas Tag Team Title history] At wrestling-titles.com</ref>\n*'''[[National Wrestling Alliance|NWA Rocky Top]]'''\n**NWA Rocky Top Heavyweight Championship (1 time)<ref>[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/tn/knoxville/nwa-rt/nwa-rt-h.html NWA Rocky Top Heavyweight Title history] At wrestling-titles.com</ref>\n*'''[[National Wrestling Alliance|NWA Wrestle Birmingham]]'''\n**[[NWA Alabama Heavyweight Championship]] ([[NWA Alabama Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=\"wrestling-titles.com\">[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/al/al-h.html NWA Alabama Heavyweight Title history] At wrestling-titles.com</ref>\n*'''[[Pacific Northwest Wrestling]]'''\n**[[NWA Pacific Northwest Tag Team Championship]] ([[NWA Pacific Northwest Tag Team Championship#Title history|3 times]]) \u2013 with [[Brett Sawyer]]<ref>[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/pnw/nwa/pnw-t.html NWA Pacific Northwest Tag Team Title history] At wrestling-titles.com</ref>\n*'''Pennsylvania Championship Wrestling''' 14 times\n**PCW Tag Team Championship (1 time) \u2013 with [[Jimmy Del Ray]]<ref name=\"Titles\">{{cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2000|edition=4th | isbn=0-9698161-5-4 }}</ref>\n*'''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n**PWI ranked him # '''318''' of the 500 best singles wrestlers of the [[PWI Years]] in 2003<ref name=PWIYears500>{{cite news|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated Top 500 of the PWI Years: 318 Dr. Tom Prichard|work=[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]|publisher=Sports and Entertainment publications LLC|location=Blue Bell, [[Pennsylvania]], [[United States]]|id=June 2003|page=45|date=May 21, 2003}}</ref>\n**PWI ranked him # '''73''' of the 100 best tag teams of the PWI Years, with [[Jimmy Del Ray]] and [[Stan Lane]] in 2003.<ref name=PWIYears100>{{cite news|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated Top 100 Tag Teams of the PWI Years: 17 The Heavenly Bodies |work=[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]|publisher=Sports and Entertainment publications LLC|location=Blue Bell, [[Pennsylvania]], [[United States]]|id=November 2003|page=20|date=October 18, 2003}}</ref>\n*'''''Ring Around The Northwest Newsletter'''''\n**Tag Team of the Year (1984) <small>with Brett Sawyer</small><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kayfabememories.com/Regions/pnw/pnw16-2.htm |title=Regional Territories: PNW #16 Page #2 |author=Rodgers, Mike |date=2004 |website=KayfabeMemories.com |publisher= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n*'''[[Continental Championship Wrestling|Southeastern Championship Wrestling / Continental Championship Wrestling / Continental Wrestling Federation]]'''\n**[[CWF Heavyweight Championship]] ([[CWF Heavyweight Championship#Title history|3 times]])<ref name=CWFHeavy>[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/tn/knoxville/cwf/cwf-h.html CWF Heavyweight Title (Alabama/Knoxville) history] At wrestling-titles.com</ref>\n**[[NWA Alabama Heavyweight Championship]] ([[NWA Alabama Heavyweight Championship#Title history|2 times]])<ref name=\"wrestling-titles.com\"/>\n**[[NWA Southeast United States Junior Heavyweight Championship]] ([[NWA Southeast United States Junior Heavyweight Championship#Title history|5 times]])<ref>[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/al/secw/se-us-j.html NWA United States Junior Heavyweight Title (Southeast/Continental) history] At wrestling-titles.com</ref>\n*'''[[Smoky Mountain Wrestling]]'''\n**[[SMW Tag Team Championship]] ([[SMW Tag Team Championship#Title history|8 times]]) \u2013 with [[Stan Lane]] (5) and Jimmy Del Ray (3)<ref name=SMWTag>{{cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2000|edition=4th |chapter= (Tennessee) Knoxville: Smokey Mountain Wrestling Tag Team Title|isbn=0-9698161-5-4}}</ref><ref>[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/tn/knoxville/smw/smw-t.html SMW Tag Team Title history] At wrestling-titles.com</ref>\n*'''[[United States Wrestling Association]]'''\n**[[Memphis Wrestling Southern Heavyweight Championship|USWA Southern Heavyweight Championship]] ([[Memphis Wrestling Southern Heavyweight Championship#Title history|6 times]])<ref name=USWASouth>[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/tn/uswa/uswa-s-h.html USWA Southern Heavyweight Title history] At wrestling-titles.com</ref>\n**[[NWA Texas Heavyweight Championship|USWA Texas Heavyweight Championship]] ([[NWA Texas Heavyweight Championship#Title history|2 times]])<ref name=TexasBook>{{cite book| last1=Will | first1=Gary | first2=Royal | last2= Duncan | title=Wrestling Title Histories: professional wrestling champions around the world from the 19th century to the present | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2000 | location=Pennsylvania | chapter=Texas: NWA Texas Heavyweight Title [Von Erich] | isbn=0-9698161-5-4 | pages=268\u2013269}}</ref><ref name=USWATexas>{{cite web | url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/tx/tx-h.html | title= NWA Texas Heavyweight Title | accessdate=March 30, 2017 | work=Wrestling-Titles}}</ref>\n**[[USWA World Tag Team Championship]] ([[USWA World Tag Team Championship#Title history|1 time]]) \u2013 with Jimmy Del Ray<ref>{{cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2000|edition=4th |chapter= (Tennessee) Memphis: United States Wrestling Association Tag Team Title|isbn=0-9698161-5-4 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/tn/uswa/uswa-t.html USWA World Tag Team Title history] At wrestling-titles.com</ref>\n*'''United Wrestling Association'''\n**UWA Southern Heavyweight Championship (1 time)\n**UWA Texas Heavyweight Championship (1 time)\n*'''[[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]]'''\n**[[World Tag Team Championship|WWF Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of World Tag Team Champions|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Chris Candido|Skip]]<ref name=WWFTag>[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/wwe/wwf-t.html WWWF/WWF/WWE World Tag Team Title history] At wrestling-titles.com</ref><ref name=WWF9099Book/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==